EVR AAPL Thesis: While we understand iPhone units (and sales) will remain muted through FY20 (5G launch), the narrative has and continues to shift towards services and a higher mix of recurring revenue for AAPL. Key levers for upside include: a) services growing double-digits with potential acceleration given new revenue streams, b) gross margins inflecting higher for the remainder of the year given easing commodity costs and better leverage, c) cap allocation enables 2-4% share reduction, and d) wearables sales inflect higher and have better margins. Wearables will become an important growth vector given both Watch & Airpods are at relatively low install base penetration. **Contact us for our Wearables model in excel** 1 Year Price History Wearables 101: The wearables business includes sales of the Apple Watch, AirPods, Apple TV, HomePod, Beats, iPod Touch, and various accessories. Currently, we estimate Watch is the largest product with ~52% revenue share in FY19 followed by Airpods with ~26% share. Going forward, we think Airpods will be the largest Wearables product in FY23 (~48% of revenue). Sizing Up The Wearables Market: Since the release of the Apple Watch in April 2015, Appleâ€™s wearables business has grown from ~$6B in FY14 to ~$24B in FY19. We think the Wearables business can sustain a growth rate in the 20-30% range and hit exceed $60B in Source: FactSet revenue in FY23 (Consensus at $44B in FY22). Our $64B FY23 Wearables revenue estimate assumes Airpods sustain a 50% CAGR through FY23 and Watch grows at a 20% CAGR (vs. 37% FY15- FY19). At ~$64B in revenue, we estimate Wearables would generate ~$3.00 in earnings vs. FY19 contribution of $1.06. The ~$2.00 in incremental Wearables earnings would represent growth of ~17% vs. Appleâ€™s FY19 EPS of $11.89. Low penetration relative to iPhone install base: We estimate the install base for the Apple Watch and AirPods are at 75M & 50M, respectively. Our estimates imply the install base for Airpods & Apple Watch is less than 10% of the iPhone install base. The low relative install bases should support continued high growth as iPhone owners become buyers of AirPods and Apple Watch. Morgan estimates. 2 58 Samik Chatterjee, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-212) 622 0798                  15 November 2019 samik.x.chatterjee@jpmorgan.com Advertising is following consumers to mobile platforms; opens up an underappreciated opportunity for Apple We believe advertising dollars, which currently are still largely spent on traditional formats and through traditional mediums, will slowly migrate to gain a larger presence on mobile platforms where consumers are spending most of their screen time. Apple with its large installed base of close to 1bn iPhone users and significantly more than 1bn users across its different devices, remains underappreciated in our view relative to its positioning to leverage this shift in advertising dollars. In this report we look at the different services through which Apple can drive higher advertising revenues. Apple has been exploring advertising through Apple Search Ads Apple has more recently discussed seeing good growth in advertising revenues, including posting the highest advertising revenue ever in the latest quarter. The advertising revenue that Apple is generating currently stems from Apple Search Ads on the App Store. Starting in late 2016, Apple started to suggest applications in response to keyword searches in the App Store, which would be shown at the top of the search results. The positioning of an application at the top of the search results (explicitly marked as an ad) in response to searches mimicks the Google Search advertising model and has allowed Apple to ramp up on an advertising business. Figure 1: Apple Search Ads Note: Image displayed is a screenshot from Apple's App Store. Source: Apple. See an opportunity to expand monetization further on the App Store Apple has restricted itself to positioning only one advertisement/suggestion per keyword search from a consumer on the App Store. We believe there is an opportunity to ramp it further and expand to more than one advertisement without necessarily impacting the consumer experience in the future. Although subsequent suggestions would not allow for similar ASP metrics as the first suggestion in response to the keyword search, we still see a step up in the monetization opportunity; particularly given the advertisement is close to point of sale itself. 3 59 Samik Chatterjee, CFA                                        North America Equity Research (1-212) 622 0798                                             15 November 2019 samik.x.chatterjee@jpmorgan.com Internet paid search is $100 bn+ revenue opportunity market To provide some context about the revenue opportunity, internet paid searches account for a ~$100 bn market and are growing in relevance as it is expected to grow ~8% per annum from 2018 to 2020. With consumption of content moving increasingly towards mobile platforms, we expect the strong growth in advertisement spend on mobile platforms will continue. Interestingly, Alphabet highlighted on its recent earnings call the shift of traffic to mobile platforms as well as higher acquisition cost of traffic on mobile platforms relative to traditional desktops (â€œThe sites TAC rate increased year-over-year primarily due to the impact of the ongoing shift to mobile, which carries higher TACâ€, Alphabet 3Q19 earnings call). Apple accounts for > 15% of global internet paid search market already Apple does not direct advertisements relative to paid search outside of the App Store, instead getting monetized by Google for directing traffic to their search engine. The strong market position that iPhones have globally, particularly in the US, drives Google to be willing to pay a hefty sum to be the default search engine for the traffic from iOS devices. Googleâ€™s total traffic acquisition cost of $30 bn annually includes roughly $14 bn of annualized traffic acquisition costs from distribution partners, which include Apple. Assuming typical gross margin of ~55% and that Apple accounts for 65% of the TAC paid by Google to distribution partners, implies that Apple supports $17 bn of advertising revenue for Google â€“ which equates to around 17% of global advertising revenue dedicated to paid searches. New services, led by Apple TV+, and to a lesser extent Apple Arcade and Apple Card should allow services growth to accelerate further in FY20 and FY21. Notably, we forecast contracting Services gross margins going forward (63.4% in FY20; 62.6% in FY21), due in part to the inclusion of Apple TV+ in our Services model, yet sequential growth in high margin Services like App Store and iCloud could act as a more meaningful offset than we currently model. (+/-) Wearables continue to lead growth. Many investors attributed 50% wearables growth in the June quarter to shorter lead times as demand caught up with supply, however a second quarter in a row of 50%+ Y/Y growth and the fact that Apple is beating AirPods forecasts weekly suggests strong double-digit growth is sustainable. Said another way, we believe Apple Watch and AirPods penetration among the iPhone installed base remains far below mature levels, and considering 3 of every 4 Apple Watch customers are new to the device, expect a long growth runway going forward. We forecast broad-based strength of the Wearables portfolio in FY20, with Apple Watch revenue growth of 24% Y/Y (due in part to the Series 5 launch), AirPods growth of 107% Y/Y (fueled by AirPods Pro at a higher ASP), Apple TV+ growth of 12% Y/Y (aided by the launch of Apple TV+) and all other Wearables, Home and Accessories growth of 5% Y/Y, resulting in total Wearables, Home and Accessories growth of 43% Y/Y in FY20 vs. 41% Y/Y in FY19. (AAPL) Foot and Web Traffic Rundown â€“ iPhone 11 Launch Exceeding Expectationsâ€¦ Our analysis of store foot traffic data in the US and website traffic globally indicates that customer interest for iPhone 11 is tracking better than the XS last year. Model level analysis of website data also shows that high-end flagship models are performing well with no substantial evidence of customer downshifting. We think this sets up iPhone performance to come in ahead of conservative Street expectations for the September quarter. This is important for investors given that the September Street consensus iPhone estimate assumes a 10% Y/Y decline (42.4m units). Our estimate is 42.5m â€“ in line with consensus. While weâ€™re not changing our numbers, we think there is a meaningful positive bias heading into September quarter results and December guidance on Appleâ€™s earnings call Wednesday. In our 9/24 report â€œUnderappreciated Position for 5G + Services Expansion = Buy Rating,â€ we outlined our view that the Street was too conservative on iPhone units in FYâ€™20 and meaningfully underestimating Appleâ€™s position for the 5G cycle in FYâ€™21. Our positivity on FYâ€™20 was more driven by mid-range devices with the bulk of our differentiation versus Street numbers coming in the back half of FYâ€™20. Now we think there can be upside from a â€œbetter than fearedâ€ iPhone 11 cycle beginning now. Our biggest differentiation versus Street consensus remains our view on iPhone units in FYâ€™21 driven by 5G. The positive performance of iPhone 11 (the last all-4G cycle) now builds a nice bridge to 5G and we think investors should get involved now. We reiterate our Buy rating on the shares and raising our Price Target to $285/share (or 17.9x our base business FYâ€™20 EPS estimate) based on potential for upside to iPhone units in FYâ€™20. Store Traffic Shows iPhone 11 Launch Having Early Successâ€¦ Our analysis of customer foot traffic across Apple and wireless carrier stores in the US shows that the iPhone 11 launch is having early success. In aggregate, we see that stores saw a 37% increase in traffic on iPhone 11 launch day versus a 32% increase for the iPhone XS launch last year. We see customer interest on launch day as a strong early indicator for how demand will track for the remainder of the annual product cycle. Our Methodologyâ€¦ SafeGraph is a data service that dynamically tracks visitor counts across retail locations and other points of interest. There are a number of factors in play that give us confidence that iPhone replacement cycles may be in the process of stabilizing. First, we believe demand in China continues to improve, with smartphone data from the Chinese government pointing to international vendor (of which we believe Apple is 90%+) shipment growth of over 25% Y/Y in the September quarter (Exhibit 4), and China smartphone installed base data showing that Apple gained Y/Y installed base share for a 9th consecutive month in September (Exhibit 5). Second, the earlier launch of all 3 new iPhone models (creating an easier compare) and relative outperformance of new model shipments this year vs. last per our iPhone shipping tracker (Exhibit 6 and Exhibit 7) tells us that new models will be a more significant contributor to C2H19 estimates than in C2H18. Third, iPhone builds are increasing, rather than decreasing, through mid-October, as demand expectations appear to be outperforming early forecasts from the supply chain. And while the risk of iPhone build cuts remain as is the case seasonally near year-end, our new September and December quarter unit forecasts of 44.5M (from 43M) and 66.75M (from 64M), respectively, remain ~7% below our Greater China Tech Hardware team's iPhone build forecasts, reflecting some conservatism. Net, our new FY20 iPhone shipment forecast of 190M (from 182M) assumes that replacement cycles stabilize around 3.7 years, which still represents a near structural ceiling relative to 4 year notebook replacement cycles (Exhibit 8). ...but lower ASPs act as an offset, resulting in largely unchanged iPhone revenue estimates. While we increase our near-term iPhone unit estimates, we also decrease our ASP estimates to $733 (from $752), $757 (from $789), and $706 (from $736) in F4Q19, F1Q20 and FY20, respectively, to account for the $50-100 cut to iPhone 11 prices (relative to the iPhone XR launch last year) and relative outperformance of the iPhone 11 in markets like China, where the Jiguang data shows the iPhone 11 representing 0.26% of the iPhone installed base in China vs. 0.14% and 0.06% for the iPhone 11 Pro Max and iPhone 11 Pro, respectively (Exhibit 9). Similarly, data from the iPhone grey market in China shows pricing for the 64GB and 256GB iPhone 11 SKUs has held up moreso than for the iPhone 11 Pro or 11 Pro Max, which helps confirm the relative outperformance of Apple's lower priced new model iPhone (Exhibit 10). Net, while our iPhone unit estimates move higher each quarter through FY20, our ASP estimates fall by 2-4%, resulting in iPhone revenue of $32.7B, $50.3B and $134.4B in F4Q19, F1Q20 and FY20, respectively, which is largely unchanged from our prior estimates. We'd note that the ASP deferral from the bundling of the free offer for Apple TV+ (as discuss in our recently published Insight note) was already embedded in our iPhone ASP estimates, so these changes are only reflective of our new mix expectations. We expect Wearables and App Store to continue outperforming. While these two segments collectively represented just 20% of Apple's revenue mix in FY17, we estimate they will account for over 100% of Apple's revenue growth in FY19 and represent over 30% of revenue in FY20. Earlier this week, Luxshare (covered by Yunchen Tsai), a key AirPods manufacturer, beat expectations on the back of stronger than expected AirPods volume, which we believe is a sustainable trend following the launch of the second-gen AirPods in March, and a rumored third- gen noise-cancelling AirPods potentially before year end. On the Services side, 3152 data from Sensor Tower shows App Store net revenue grew ~22% Y/Y in the September quarter, representing 4 points of outperformance vs. our +18% Y/Y estimate, and a 3.5 point growth acceleration from 18.4% Y/Y growth the June quarter (Exhibit 11), the strongest quarter-over-quarter growth acceleration since the December 2015 quarter. Our updated September quarter Services estimate of $12.4B (+17.2% Y/Y) now accounts for this outperformance (slightly offset by more significant a la carte music and video declines), which is likely not accounted for in consensus estimates that forecast a continued deceleration in Services revenue growth (Exhibit 12). Looking forward, App Store comps continue to ease into the December quarter (most notably in China), and we expect contributions from new Services such as Apple TV+ to begin impacting the model as early as the December 2019 quarter as well, resulting in our forecast for 17.7% Y/Y growth next quarter (Exhibit 13). 3163

Net, TV+ adds 2 points to our Services revenue growth forecast in FY20 (to $55.1B in revenue, from $54.2B prior; Exhibit 6). Beyond FY20, we see Apple TV+ contributing slightly more than 1 point on average to Services growth annually through FY23 (to $89.8B in revenue, from $85.7B prior; Exhibit 7). Assuming a straight-line amortization schedule, we estimate Apple TV+ content costs (expensed as COGS) ramp from $401M in FY20, to $4.5B in FY25 (Exhibit 8 and Exhibit 9), which dilutes Services gross margins by 11bps in FY20, and up to 125bps in FY23 (to 61.7%, from 63.0% previously; Exhibit 10), but the higher Services revenue base more than offsets Services margin dilution such that Services gross profit dollars increase by 2.5%, on average, between FY20 and FY23. All of our detailed Apple TV+ drivers and assumptions can be found here: Diving Into Our Apple TV+ Assumptions. Key Debate 2: How material is the near-term headwind from bundling a one year free Apple TV+ offer with device purchases and ramping video content costs? We worked closely with Morgan Stanleyâ€™s Global Valuation, Accounting and Tax (GVAT) team to embed ASC 606 revenue recognition and streaming content accounting standards into our Apple TV+ model. At the heart of this debate are two issues. First, the accounting treatment of bundling a one year free offer to Apple TV+ with the purchase of any iPhone, iPad, Mac, iPod Touch or Apple TV, where Apple will likely have to defer ~$57 per iPhone sold to be amortized as Apple TV+ Services revenue over the year the free trial is active, but only for customers who Apple expects to redeem the free Apple TV+. We assume the Apple TV+ free offer adoption is in-line to lower relative to iCloud adoption in its first year, starting at 5-10% conversion in F1Q20 and reaching as high as 40%, for some customers by F4Q20 (Exhibit 12). These assumptions imply Apple will likely defer $900M net ($1.6B gross) of hardware ASP in F4Q19-F4Q20, resulting in a 20bps headwind to FY20 total revenue (Exhibit 13). More details on the mechanics of how this flows through the P&L can be found in Exhibit 14. The second aspect of this debate relates to how much Apple is spending on content at the launch of Apple TV+, and how those costs are accounted for. Media companies can account for video content costs in several ways (see: Media, Internet & GVAT: Streaming Changes Everything - Even The Accounting Rules); we assume that Apple capitalizes all content costs on the balance sheet and then amortizes the costs as Services COGS in a straight line method over a 3 year period. Our bottom-up analysis of costs implies the programs set to launch November 1st correspond to $585M of production costs with only $35M accounted for as COGS in the December 2019 quarter. We assume Apple rolls out 2 shows per month after November corresponding to a total of over $2B of total production costs by FY20 year-end and $401M of amortized costs included in Services COGS in FY20 (Exhibit 15), resulting in a 1.9% headwind to FY20 EPS, which is now accounted for in our model. For Apple TV+ to have a more material impact to our near term estimates, we'd have to assume 1) Apple TV+ production costs are significantly higher at the launch of the Service, and/or 2) more users redeem the Apple 12 month free offer with the purchase of a device. In the latter case, FCF is unchanged and Apple would exit FY20 with a higher base of users to convert to paid subscribers, 3352 putting upward pressure on our outer year estimates. See Exhibit 16 for a sensitivity analysis of how changes to our Apple TV+ accounting assumptions impact Apple's near-term revenue and EPS. Key Debate 3: Is Apple TV+ accretive or dilutive to overall estimates? Apple has publicly commented "We do not expect the introduction of Apple TV+, including the accounting treatment for the service, to have a material impact on our financial results." Our analysis is largely consistent with that conclusion. We estimate that in FY20, the incremental revenue from Apple TV+ will not be enough to offset the hardware deferral, which when combined with over $600M in incremental COGS and OpEx from Apple TV+ (we assume Apple TV+ OpEx as a % of revenue is twice the Apple corporate level) results in a 1.9% headwind to FY20 EPS (Exhibit 17). However, we expect Apple TV+ to become accretive by 0.8% in FY21 as previously deferred hardware revenue is amortized as Apple TV+ revenue and free Apple TV+ users convert to paid subscribers, accelerating user growth, which more than offsets the ramp in content costs and operating expenses associated with Apple TV+. Beyond FY21, we expect Apple TV+ to become more accretive to revenue and gross profit dollar growth, but ramping TV+ costs imply +0.6% accretion in FY22, and +0.3% accretion in FY23. Raising PT to $289 (from $247) to reflect TV+ ramp and peaking iPhone replacement cycle. Our new $289 price target is derived from a sum-of-the-parts analysis now based on FY21 estimates rather than FY20, as we believe FY21 estimates better capture the sustainable earnings power as new Services, like TV+, ramp and iPhone returns to growth as replacement cycles peak and 5G drives device upgrades. To arrive at our price target we assume a 2.9x EV/Sales multiple on FY21 Product revenue of $233.3B, which represents a blend of an HPQ and MSFT multiple, and a 7.1x EV/Sales multiple on $65.8B of Services revenue, representing the median multiple of a group of 8 platform/services/internet companies, resulting in a 3.8x blended target EV/Sales multiple. Our $289 price target implies Apple trades at 18.7x our new FY21 EPS of $15.46 (up from $15.34 previously), and 23.2x FY20 EPS of $12.44 (down from $12.68 previously), meaningfully higher than Apple's trailing 2-year P/E of 16.3x in light of Services representing over â…“ of total gross profit mix (set to climb to 44% by FY23) vs. just 20% 2 years ago. Notably, our base case FY21 iPhone revenue growth reflects stabilizing, but not shrinking, replacement cycles during the 5G iPhone cycle which increasingly appears conservative given constructive demand data points early in the iPhone 11 cycle. 3363 Key Exhibits Exhibit 1: Our analysis suggests Apple TV+ is worth ~$3 per share in our base case, or ~1% of our $289 price target. Looking forward, we believe that a confluence of factors will drive further performance out of the business (and the share price). Specifically, we believe that Street views of the iPhone business are too conservative â€“ particularly for the pending 5G cycle beginning in late next year. Further, we believe their Services business is underappreciated by investors. That business offers a massive expansion in the potential TAM addressed by Apple. Weâ€™re initiating research coverage of the shares with a $260 Price Target and a Buy rating. Key elements of our thesis includeâ€¦ Appleâ€™s â€œFranchiseâ€ iPhone Position Is Secure. Our analysis of ListenFirst digital and social engagement metrics coming out of the iPhone 11/11 Pro launch shows brand engagement is higher than ever for Apple. ListenFirst's Digital Audience Rating was higher for the iPhone 11 than the XS/XR launch last year and Samsung's Galaxy S10 launch in February. iPhone search interest is also showing solid growth over last year. We don't see loyalty waning for Apple as the iOS platform creates incredible stickiness among customers. Also, most of industry profitability comes from the high-end of the smartphone market where Apple holds a dominant position. We donâ€™t expect competitors will make a significant dent in Appleâ€™s iPhone franchise over at least the near- or intermediate-term. Street iPhone Estimates Are Too Conservative. Given the advanced technology and components, 5G devices will be high-end devices (where Apple holds dominant share). Our analysis (built on pricing data by model) of competition and market share across price levels shows Apple's share increases as prices go higher. Street expectations call for 190m units for the FYâ€™21 5G iPhone cycle, or 9% below the 6- year average unit volumes for prior iPhone cycles. For example, Apple sold 212m, 217m, and 218m, in FYâ€™16, FYâ€™17, and FYâ€™18 (i.e. the iPhone 6S/6S+, 7/7+, and 8/8+/X cycles, respectively). We think the 190m figure is too low given: 1) thereâ€™s a larger and aging installed base of iPhone coming up for refresh â€“ even if upgrade cycles are 3+ years; 2) 5G will be big â€“ the marketing machines at every wireless operator will be driving a 5G message with consumers; 3) the 5G iPhone cycle will offer more significant product differentiation versus prior cycles; 4) worldwide smartphone rates are higher versus prior cycles; and 5) Appleâ€™s mid-range offering will expand their TAM modestly and entice buyers to refresh more quickly. The negative offset is a softer Chinese economy vis-Ã -vis these prior iPhone cycles. As we gauge these factors, we think that a consensus unit shipment figure of 190m is too low. Instead, weâ€™re modelling for 208m units shipped in FYâ€™21. A Significantly Expanding Services TAM. We think the Services opportunity is underestimated broadly by investors. No, Mid-Range Phones Wonâ€™t Cannibalize the High-End. Thereâ€™s a debate in the industry right now about whether Appleâ€™s introduction of lower-priced models will negatively affect total sales and cause customers to downshift out of high-end models. We donâ€™t see customer downshifting becoming a problem for Apple for two reasons: 1) they already sell a whole host of previous generation devices at lower prices so these price points arenâ€™t really new; and 2) our analysis of smartphone spending versus income suggests that consumers tend to buy the most advanced smartphone they can afford. Thereâ€™s Still a Growth Path Left for iPhoneâ€¦ Premium Phone Penetration Isnâ€™t Over. We think thereâ€™s still a growth path left for iPhone and the premium smartphone category overall, even in the face of maturing mobile markets worldwide. For the last 12 years, the smartphone industry was riding waves of growth in global adoption. This was great for Apple and great for most players in the industry because it opened up new categories of customers every year. Given the global success and demand for the smartphone as a computing platform, most global markets charged rapidly toward full adoption. Of course, global smartphone adoption is flattening out. While global smartphone penetration is now 75%+, premium smartphones still represent a much smaller part of the market for smartphones broadly (~16%). Further, premium penetration has increased from 13% in 2012 to 16% in 2018. Looking forward, we think that premium smartphone penetration can continue to tick up over time as economies expand, infrastructure gets built, and more and more people embrace mobile devices with advanced capabilities. 2. Based on our bottom-up iPhone gross margin model by SKU, we estimate that gross profit dollars per unit for the latest refreshed mid-range devices are near the overall blended iPhone average for the company. As long as the ratio of high-end flagship phones to legacy models remains the same, Apple wonâ€™t see any gross margin pressure by selling more mid-range phones. When Apple raised prices on flagship models in September 2017, it essentially gave it the room to sell older legacy models at reduced prices (and lower gross profitability) for longer. Currently, we estimate that Apple makes around $470 in gross profit dollars per unit for flagship models, $153/unit for legacy models, and $253/unit for mid-range models. The total blended iPhone gross profit dollars per unit is also close to the mid-range number at $262. 7. Consumers Will Still Buy the Highest Spec Smartphone They Can Afford. We believe thereâ€™s still strong evidence that smartphone customers will pay for value and will typically gravitate toward the highest spec smartphone assuming they can afford it. We donâ€™t think it will be very common for an affluent customer to move to a lower spec phone because itâ€™s cheaper. We think this also holds true across different classes of society, the specs are just lower. Years of smartphone industry data support this view, in our opinion, across developed and emerging markets. We find that annual smartphone spending per capita has a tight linear relationship with GDP per capita. Further, we can also note that growth in smartphone spending follows a similar growth curve to GDP per capita in both developed and emerging markets. Based on this dynamic, we think Appleâ€™s mid-range offerings are more targeted at providing an Apple product for more segments of the market and capturing additional volume as middle-class consumers expand worldwide. Further, we donâ€™t think thereâ€™s as much risk as the Street perceives that high-end flagship Apple customers will â€œdownshiftâ€ into lower models. 8. Looking forward, one element of the trade-in program that will be particularly incremental is China. The new China program was only fully implemented last November. TV+ â€“ Apple Has a Unique and Underestimated Position in the TV Ecosystem. We think Apple has a solid position in OTT Streaming Video Services, even among a crowded field of players. As a diversified technology company, Apple is in a unique position as it enters into original content. We think Appleâ€™s installed base of 1.4 Billion devices worldwide gives it a significant reach and advantage over many competitors. Out of the major OTT streaming services (AT&T, Amazon, Apple, Comcast, Google, Disney, Netflix), Apple is one of very few players that have a major footprint in most layers of the ecosystem (content, streaming service, device hardware, and operating system). As it launches TV+, it has original content, an OTT streaming service, an entrenched OS/platform to stream content, and design and sell many of the devices subscribers use to watch (iPhone, iPad, MacBook, Apple TV). This gives Apple a unique advantage for its OTT streaming service launching November 1. 11. The 2019 Launch Year Was Strategic â€“ Third-Party Content Finally Gets Unlocked. In our view, Apple has been planning a TV streaming service for quite a while and focused on 2019 as the most opportune time to enter the market. This is the year when many existing content right deals expired. Content owners were freed from the â€œdirect-to-consumerâ€ distribution restrictions in their previous contracts with traditional Pay-TV providers. That gave Apple the opportunity to garner mindshare with third-party content owners as it created its â€œApple Channelsâ€ offering. We expect that Apple has been talking to all the major content owners to make sure any new contracts were void of â€œdirect-to-consumerâ€ restrictions that would prevent them from monetizing within the Apple ecosystem. 12. Monetizing Their Own Content isnâ€™t Appleâ€™s Only Way to Make Money. We believe that Appleâ€™s strategy for Apple TV+ and its original content is to use it as an anchor for OTT video streaming on its platform. At first, Apple TV+ will serve as an added benefit, but it will not be the only way that Apple will generate streaming video revenue. Appleâ€™s priority will be to use its original content to attract viewers to its platform, giving viewers a better reason to subscribe to other services or buy/ rent content through iOS instead of a third-party platform. Hence, we think Apple chose to price its subscription at $4.99/month (a discount to Disney+ at $6.99/ month), leaving users with more money to subscribe to Apple Channels. The remaining non-Apple original part of the platform will work a lot like App Store and News+ where Apple has a wholesale/retail relationship with third-party content owners selling subscriptions through the platform. Further, given the concentration of industry profitability at the higher-end of the market, we think a commanding position in the premium market is really required for a device vendor to have a lasting presence. Obviously, a number of smartphone companies have fallen from grace over the years (Nokia, Motorola, Blackberry, and HTC), typically because they stop innovating after a few hit products and fail to maintain mindshare at the higher-end. We think Apple stands out from the pack of low-differentiation smartphone vendors trading market share at the lower-end. We see its â€œfranchiseâ€ position in the premium segment of the smartphone market as durable and secure. Of course, the stickiness of its iOS platform is a big part of the recipe for Apple. The full stack solution analyzes a constant flow of patient data and offers recommendations or 'nudges,' which use AI to maximize efficacy. Greater efficacy leads to increased customer satisfaction, lower costs, and improved outcomes. We believe this model is similar to what Apple is attempting with activity tracking and heart health. Apple is already leveraging AI to nudge users with custom recommendations to 'close their ringsâ€™, which entails hitting calorie, activity, and stand goals. Meanwhile, Apple is launching a Heart & Movement Study that aims to discover the interplay between activity levels and heart health. DexCom (Continuous Glucose Monitoring Devices): DexCom discussed a potential value-based economic model that we believe Apple could use to monetize its own healthcare offerings. DexCom has worked with UnitedHealthcare to study the potential reduction in overall cost of care for Type-2 diabetes patients through continuous glucose monitoring (CGM). While DexCom suggested UnitedHealthcare will likely keep study results internal, management mentioned that early indications of CGM adoption driving improved patient outcomes and cost of care reductions are promising. Further, management indicated they are exploring a model whereby DexCom could realize a 10-15% take rate on a payorâ€™s per-patient cost savings driven by CGM utilization. This value-based model is similar to what we theorized as a monetization method for Apple's healthcare efforts. If Apple can demonstrate a tangible reduction in patient costs through the use of its health offerings (Watch, Health app, Health Records, etc.), Apple could charge payors a take rate on those cost savings. Though DexCom and UnitedHealthcare remain in early stages of exploring these capabilities, the learnings could ultimately be applied to UnitedHealthcare's own partnership with Apple, potentially accelerating the timeline of Apple health monetization. Lastly, we expected improved camera and battery technology but the improvements in photo quality and battery life were very significant - for instance 4 to 5 hour longer iPhone 11 Pro / Max battery life compares to less than one hour average improvement in the last two product cycles. Importantly, recent survey results show camera quality and battery life are two of the top three features consumers consider when upgrading their smartphone (Exhibit 7). New Services pricing / bundling more aggressive than expected. Apple opened today's special event with a focus on Services including key details for the Apple Arcade and Apple TV+ launches. Most surprising was Apple's pricing strategy for Apple TV+. Not only is Apple undercutting other OTT video services by offering Apple TV+ at $4.99/month (for up to 6 users, with a 7-day free trial; Exhibit 8), they are also offering a year of TV+ for free to customers that purchase any iPhone, iPad, Mac, Apple TV or iPod Touch. While this may dampen near-term revenue contribution expectations for the streaming video service, it allows Apple to effectively build a base of millions of free-trial users that can convert to paying users as Apple ramps and rolls out new content beyond the 8 original series expected at the November 1st launch. With Apple Arcade, many of the details covered by the press ahead of today's event were in-line with Apple's announcement today, and Apple Arcade will be available to customers in over 150 countries for $4.99/month starting September 19th with a free 1-month trial. iPhone 11 addresses key customer pain points in camera and battery. According to our survey of this year's Morgan Stanley North America summer intern class, battery life and camera quality ranked as the #1 and #3 most important features when purchasing a new smartphone (Exhibit 7), which is broadly consistent with past survey work we have done with a wider sample size (see here). The new iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max add a rear-facing triple camera with 4x optical zoom, rivaling high-end smartphone competitors, and a rear-facing dual camera on the lower priced iPhone 11. Similarly, the iPhone 11 Pro and 11 Pro Max features 4 and 5 hours of additional battery life relative to their respective predecessors, the iPhone XS and iPhone XS Max. On the pricing front, Apple kept pricing of the highest end SKUs consistent with last year, but lowered the starting price of the iPhone 11 by $50 at each storage capacity compared to XR a year ago, while lowering the price of the iPhone XR, 8 Plus and 8 by a minimum of $150 which compares to a lower $100 price cut a year ago (Exhibit 9). With the trade-in of a 2-year-old device, customers can get $300 (iPhone 8) to $400 (iPhone X) in credit towards a new iPhone purchase, which we expect will continue to be a popular program to help subsidize iPhone upgrades (June Q iPhone trade-in volume was 5x the year ago quarter). While we're not changing our FY20 iPhone unit (-2% Y/Y) and ASP (also -2% Y/Y) assumptions at this point, we see the most upside to units given elongated replacement cycles, easier compares in China, and the significant camera and battery upgrades in the iPhone 11 line-up. Functional improvement come to the iPad and Apple Watch. Today's iPad and Apple Watch announcements were less about revolutionary hardware upgrades and more about subtle feature enhancements that will drive an improved experience when paired with the new iPadOS and WatchOS announced at WWDC in June. For example, the Apple Watch Series 5 will feature a new display that is always on, allowing you to see important data on the home screen at all 5552 times, as well as new compass app that developers can tap into, all without an impact to battery life. Watch pricing is consistent with last year's Watch Series 4 launch with a broader array of case and band designs. Apple also lowered the price of the 2-year-old Apple Watch Series 3 to just $199, in-line with the pricing of lower-end smartwatches. The new iPad takes advantage of multi-tasking features in iPadOS with a larger 10.2" retina display (vs. 9.7" previously) and 3x the pixels, 2x processor speed than the top-selling laptop on the market today. The new iPad price starts at $329, in-line with its predecessor. 5563

In the quarter, App Store,           For analyst certification and other important disclosures, Apple Music, iCloud and Apple Care all grew double digits Y/Y, while App Store        refer to the Disclosure Section, located at the end of this report. Search Ads (in the Licensing & Other line in our Services model) and Apple Pay 87 1 grew triple digits Y/Y. We still expect easing App Store comps in China as well as new Services, starting with Apple Card launching in August, to contribute incremental Services revenue in C2H19, and model Services growth accelerating to 17% Y/Y in C2H19, from 16% Y/Y in C1H19. Management confirmed that new media services, like TV+, will be revenue generating versus bundled with hardware as some investors expected, but free trials will delay the revenue ramp, likely by a quarter. (+) iPhone stabilizing as emerging markets recover and replacement cycles near peak. Emerging markets grew in the June quarter, with the BRIC countries growing 3% Y/Y after declining 25% Y/Y in F1H19, and Mainland China specifically growing Y/Y on an as reported basis and Greater China growing in CC, the biggest contributor to the 5 point improvement in iPhone revenue growth from the March quarter. We believe there is limited downside to iPhone growth near-term as replacement cycles stabilize (Exhibit 1) and approach levels of the mature PC market which has normalized at roughly a 4 year device life. Our September quarter iPhone unit estimate is unchanged at 43M, driving total iPhone revenue of $32.6B and implying the Y/Y iPhone growth trajectory continues to improve (to -11% Y/Y, from -12% Y/Y in the June Q) as we approach the next iPhone cycle. (+) Wearables becoming a meaningful growth driver. Wearables, Home and Accessories growth accelerated to 48% Y/Y (with Wearables alone growing >50% Y/Y) and now accounts for 10% of Apple revenue vs. 7% in the June 2018 quarter. When combined with Services, these two segments account for 32% of revenue that is tied to iPhone user base but not necessarily new device sales. As a result, we expect smoother revenue seasonality as evidenced by the better than expected June results (0.8% above Street) and September 2019 (2.5% above Street at the midpoint) revenue guidance. (+) Operating leverage returning to the model. The September quarter marks the first quarter since December 2017 that Apple has guided to a sequential improvement in gross margins, which we attribute to lower memory costs and an overall mix shift towards Services, where we model a gross margin of 64.3% in the September Q. Additionally, Apple guided September quarter OpEx up less than 1% Q/Q (or less than $67M) at the midpoint, the lowest Q/Q OpEx growth in a September quarter since 2013, a testament to the scalability of the revenue base (most notably Services) and cost planning after the December quarter weakness that is now flowing through the model. Management noted that they will continue to invest competitively in R&D and to support new product launches with marketing and advertising, so we don't view the September quarter OpEx guide as an indicator that future OpEx growth will take a step function lower, but rather that revenue growth is returning to the model and driving operating leverage. 88 2

Appleâ€™s current generation iPhones retail for $749-$1099. On its FQ1:19 earnings call, Apple disclosed that the iPhone install base now exceeds 900m active users. iPhone Refresh Cycle: Since the launch of the original iPhone, Apple has updated the product annually and has redesigned the iPhone every two years. The elongation of the iPhone refresh cycle has become central to the bearish narrative as recent redesigns have offered minimal incremental functionality. We think refresh demand will likely remain muted until Apple unveils a 5G compatible model (expected in 2020). iPhone Growth Trajectory: A commonly cited reason for iPhone declines is the lack of compelling new-features on the iPhone XR. Assuming this was a key driver of iPhone declines, FY16 provides a solid precedent for estimating the recovery that can be expected when the iPhone 11 is released. Apple released the iPhone 6s at the end of FY15 and it was largely a disappointment with few improvements vs. the iPhone 6. Limited demand for the 6s ultimately drove a 12% decline in FY16 iPhone revenue, slightly less than our forecasted 15% decline in FY19. iPhone revenue recovered after the release of the iPhone 7, growing 3% in FY17 and 18% in FY18 with the release of the iPhone X. Currently, we estimate iPhone revenue to be ~flat in FY20, so we are not assuming a FY20 recovery in iPhone sales following the release of the iPhone 11 as we think the refresh cycle will remain elongated until Apple releases a 5G model. We believe improved Services growth can persist through year end on further easing App Store comps in China, and into FY20 on the heels of yet-to-launch (but already announced) Services, which consensus estimates do not appear to currently take into account (Exhibit 6). Investors remain focused on key Services growth risks, including App Store take-rates, competition from cloud gaming, and slowing Google TAC payments. We've addressed these in prior research (here and here) and don't see high likelihood these factors would pressure near-term Services growth. iPhone performance in China likely to be a focus; we believe performance improved in the June quarter. We forecast 37M iPhone shipments in the June quarter (-10% Y/Y) translating to $26.2B iPhone revenue (-11% Y/Y), an improvement from a 17% Y/Y iPhone revenue decline in the March quarter. Our domestic checks remained stable through the quarter but two factors give us confidence that performance in China improved. First, according to data compiled by push-messaging service provider Jiguang, iPhone share of the China smartphone installed base increased Y/Y for the 6th consecutive month in June, growing 96bps Y/Y to 20.0%, a slight improvement from May's 51bps Y/Y installed base gains (Exhibit 7). Second, smartphone shipment data from the Chinese government show international smartphone shipments (essentially Apple and Samsung) declined only 0.9% Y/Y in the June quarter, an improvement from 46.3% Y/Y declines in the March quarter (Exhibit 8), even after incorporating international smartphone shipment declines of over 30% Y/Y in the month of June. While the Chinese government smartphone shipment data does not always correlate with data from third party providers in the US, the directional improvement is notable relative to the March quarter, giving us confidence in our June quarter iPhone forecast. Keeping September quarter estimates largely unchanged with negligible risk to revenue guidance. We forecast September quarter revenue and gross margin of $61.3B (-3% Y/Y) and 37.7% (-60bps Y/Y), respectively, which are largely unchanged from our prior forecasts and in-line-to-below consensus estimates. September quarter iPhone expectations have come down in recent weeks as supply chain analysts have cut iPhone builds to the low 40M range; however, those cuts are largely in-line with our 43M iPhone shipment estimate (-8% Y/Y). Our Greater China Tech Hardware team has a more bullish outlook and recently raised September iPhone builds by 6M units to 48M, driven by legacy model builds. Therefore, we are biased toward higher unit/lower ASP estimates in September, but believe iPhone revenue in September is likely to be relatively in- line with our $32B estimate (-13% Y/Y). On the Services side, we forecast 18% Y/Y growth in the September quarter, a deceleration from our June quarter growth forecast despite easing China gaming comps, again, implying not overly optimistic forecasts for the quarter. We see multiple catalysts into 2020 supporting our Overweight rating; PT moves to $247. The combination of negative investor sentiment, the potential for a Services acceleration in June, and a low bar for September guidance keep us positively biased into earnings. But we believe there is also a clear catalyst path beyond earnings that will help the stock re-rate towards our updated $247 price 2082 target (from $231 previously) over the next 6-9 months, making it a top pick for 2H19. In the near-term, the most important catalyst remains an acceleration in Services revenue growth in C2H19, which is not baked into consensus estimates and which will be aided by the launch (and more details, such as bundling efforts) of the Apple Card, Apple TV+, and Apple Arcade, offsetting what is usually a "sell the news" event around the September iPhone launch. Exiting 2019, we expect investors to shift focus to the potential 5G iPhone in September 2020. Historically Apple shares begin to price in significant iPhone launches (such as the iPhone 6 launch in 2014 or the iPhone X launch in 2017) up to 9 months ahead of the launch date (Exhibit 9). Importantly, the iPhone replacement cycle now stands at nearly 4 years, in-line with the mature PC market and a structural ceiling in our view. As a result, we see near-term downside to iPhone shipments as more limited than in the past and the potential for an upgrade cycle, like 5G, to have a more meaningful impact to iPhone shipment growth as compared to iPhone X, which was launched at a time when replacement cycles were lengthening due to the shift away from handset subsidies. We roll forward our valuation to FY20 estimates (from CY19) and update our SoTP-driven price target, which rises to $247 (from $231 previously; Exhibit 10). Risks to our view are 1) slowing China data in the month of June which could limit upside in the September quarter, 2) re-escalating US-China trade tensions, 3) law of large numbers catching up with the more mature services like App Store and AppleCare which could offset growth from newer services and easing Y/Y compares in China. 2093

June marked the first quarter of "easy" comps and as such, China gaming net revenue growth accelerated to 12% Y/Y, from just 2% Y/Y growth in the March quarter (Exhibit 5). Going forward, China gaming faces a -4% Y/Y and -1% Y/Y comp in the September and December 2019 quarters, respectively, suggesting China gaming growth can continue to accelerate in the back half of year. Outside of China, the US, Japan and rest of world (ROW) collectively posted gaming growth of at least 11% Y/Y in the June quarter, with the US (24% of gaming revenue) and ROW (21% of gaming revenue) facing easing comps and Japan (24% of gaming revenue) facing more difficult comps as we enter the back half of 2019. (+ / -) App Store revenue diversifying with most segments on improving trajectory. Last quarter we wrote about disconcerting growth trends in the Entertainment segment, the second largest in the App Store (at 7% of T12M App Store net revenue), which has been impacted by large entertainment companies (such as Netflix) bypassing Apple's payment platform to avoid paying the 15%/30% App Store take rate. Bears have pointed to this as a sign that other companies will follow suit (as Spotify has), putting future App Store growth at risk. In the June quarter, Entertainment growth decelerated again to just +12% Y/Y, from +26% Y/Y in the March quarter from over 100% Y/Y only one year ago, however Entertainment was only one of two segments in the top 10 segments (97% of T12M App Store net revenue) to decelerate, along with Productivity apps, the 10th largest segment in the App Store (Exhibit 6). In fact, despite Spotify taking actions to bypass the App Store, Music net revenue (3% of App Store) growth accelerated 630bps to 30% Y/Y in the June quarter, from 24% Y/Y in the March quarter. While gaming remains the core driver of App Store revenue, these other segments continue to become more meaningful contributors to the Apple Store, with the top 10 segments ex-Gaming representing 28% of App Store spend in 2Q18 vs. 25% in 2Q17 and 18% in 2Q16. (-) Trade measures between US and China potentially impacting Chinese consumer demand. On a monthly basis, total App Store net revenue growth slowed through the course of the June quarter, from 21% Y/Y growth in April, to +18% in May and +13% in June. Digging a level deeper, monthly growth trends in the US and Japan (roughly half of App Store net revenue) were either steady or accelerating through the quarter, but China net revenue growth slowed from 19% Y/Y or greater growth in April and May to just 4% Y/Y growth in June (Exhibit 7). While the comps got slightly more difficult in the month of June, slowing consumer demand in China could also tie back to more restrictive trade measures. While Apple iPhone installed base share has held up well in recent months (see the latest here), weaker consumer demand could weigh on app store engagement. We'd also highlight that our Greater China Technology Hardware analyst Sharon Shih kept new model builds unchanged this month (while slightly lowering legacy builds due to recent iOS upgrades that improve performance on installed iPhones), which gives us confidence that iPhone demand, while weak (we forecast June quarter iPhone shipments down 10% Y/Y and Sept down 8% Y/Y), is not worsening materially due to broader geopolitical issues. What to do with Apple shares at these levels. Apple shares currently trade at 15x our CY20 EPS of $13.30, a turn lower than Apple's 2-year average trailing P/E of 16.1x, and ~2 turns lower than our price target of $231 implies. This suggests that trade and regulation remain overhangs that are partially priced into shares today (see our most recent views on trade and regulation), with trade the more near term risk. While President Trump's announcement that he plans for an "extended" meeting with Chinese President Xi at next week's G20 meetings is a positive development, the possibility remains that the US will place tariffs on the remaining $300B of imports from China, which assuming Apple doesn't receive an exception, would reverberate throughout the supply chain and lead to higher prices for consumers and higher costs for Apple. While the overhang of trade risk may keep shares range bound near-term, we see two important upcoming fundamental catalysts that should drive shares toward our price target, including 1) a potential acceleration in Services revenue growth as comps ease and new services ramp, and 2) Apple's 2020 launch of a 5G iPhone, which is typically priced into shares starting 6-9 months ahead of the launch date (which we see as September 2020; Exhibit 5). Importantly, the iPhone replacement cycle is already approaching four years, near where PC replacement rates stabilized, suggesting the product is at a structural ceiling where growth trends should stabilize long- term. This dynamic sets the stock up well heading into a potential 5G upgrade cycle. We are now trimming our calendar year 2019 shipment estimates to 183 mn vs. 185 mn prior, although marked by a much more significant reduction in our CQ2-CQ4 estimates to 139.5 mn relative to 144 mn earlier (-4% annualized reduction). Looking to the out-years, we continue to forecast a return to shipment growth in C2020/C2021. Growth forecast for C2020/C2021 driven by greater spec upgrades Given the significant decline expected in iPhone shipments in C2019, we believe investor expectations are primed for continued modest decline for both the smartphone industry and iPhone shipments in the out-years. However, we believe there is an opportunity for a modest acceleration in the replacement cycle driving a return to growth for iPhone shipments in C2020/C2021, led by the significant spec upgrades expected in the September 2020 launch. Based on our discussions with Qualcomm and interpretations relative to their recent settlement with Apple, we believe all three new iPhone models to be launched in 2020 will include 5G baseband modems with support for mmWave frequencies. Additionally, discussions with 3D Sensing companies indicates a strong likelihood of adoption of world facing 3D Sensing on the iPhone models to be launched in September 2020, driving industry leading AR/VR capabilities which can be leveraged by applications (including games) custom built for the platform. Challenges in China are concerning, but Apple is not new to navigating them We are aware that iPhone demand in China is on top of investor minds given the backdrop of continued uncertainty in the US and China trade relationship, which is impacting regional macro trends and consumer spending. However, it is important to keep in mind that challenges for iPhone sales in the China market are not new and we have been witnessing declines for the last few years. As shown in Figure 2 below, iPhone shipments to China have declined -6% in 2016, -2% in 2017, and -18% in 2018 driving the total iPhone shipments in China to a meagre 40 mn or 19% of total. 3 400

Several new iOS upgrades with a focus on privacy. One of the characteristics we have long written about as a differentiating factor for Apple is its ability to vertically integrate hardware and software, which few, if any, mobile competitors can replicate. Today, CEO Tim Cook highlighted that 85% of current iOS customers are running the latest version of iOS 12 vs. just 10% adoption for the latest Android operating system, Pie. This means that roughly 90% of the Android user base cannot access the latest software features on their mobile device, putting those users at a meaningful disadvantage vs. Apple users in terms of user experience. Packaged with Apple's latest iOS update (iOS 13), users get several new features, such as Dark Mode, live radio, full voice control, a standalone Siri Shortcuts app and updated smart lists and reminder apps, updated Memoji support for iPhone 6s and newer, a combined "Find My" app that works even with devices that are asleep, and a completely redesigned and updated Apple Maps, not to mention 30% faster unlocking with FaceID and 2x the launch speed for opening apps. Additionally, Apple emphasized privacy standards by introducing features such as the "Sign in with Apple" button, which will serve as an alternative to sign-in buttons from other platforms, like Facebook and Google, where data privacy standards aren't as high as Apple's. iOS 13 also allows users to choose when to share their name and email address with the option to provide a unique random email address to third parties. iOS 13 will also help users better understand and limit location tracking while updates to HomeKit encrypt video stored in the cloud (for free). Deepening device features and products to attract more commercial users. Apple introduced new features that make iPad more appealing as a productivity device. Can Apple obtain an exclusion from the proposed final round of tariffs on US imports from China? On May 10th, the Office of the US Trade Representation proposed additional tariffs (25%) on the remaining ~$300B of goods imported from China, under Section 301 of the Trade Act of 1974. Over the course of the next month (final comments are due June 24th and a final list can be released thereafter), the proposal will go through a public comment process at which time companies can suggest certain product headings be eliminated from the final list of taxed goods. While our strategists and economists don't have these tariffs becoming policy in their base case, they believe the risk of implementation continues to rise (for more on the big picture timeline and process for tariff implementation, see here: US Public Policy, Economics, and Rates Strategy: US- China Trade: FAQs on the Possible Next Escalation). Assuming the timeline outlined by the USTR remains unchanged, Apple has roughly one month to propose removing certain product categories before the list of tariffed goods is finalized. It's important to note that Apple (and others) successfully argued their case in September 2018, when the USTR removed devices that receive and transmit voice data (which includes the Apple Watch and AirPods) from the final list of the $200B tranche of goods that saw a tariff go into effect before year end. In the event Apple is unsuccessful in persuading the USTR to remove key categories from the final list of taxed goods, Apple's representative will have to submit a request for each particular product they'd like to be excluded, and provide a rationale as to why it should be excluded from the tariff list. Assuming this is the case, Apple will likely argue that iOS users have no alternative to Apple products (i.e. to switch to an Android based smartphone or other technology product would do harm to the US consumer) and that almost all of Apple's R&D is done in the US. While conceivable, it's unclear how the USTR would view these arguments. And while the USTR has granted 125 exclusions thus far, they only apply to the first $34B round of tariffs announced in mid-2018. The exclusion process for the $200B List 3 of imported 16 2 goods has not begun yet and the process for the final round of $300B won't start until List 3 is finalized and the details for the exclusion process are announced. Nevertheless, if granted, exclusions would be retroactive to the start date of the tariffs. For more on the potential impact (and other mitigating factors) from the final round of tariffs on Apple, please see our latest views here: Tech Hardware Pulse: What Investors Are Asking: An Update on the AAPL Tariff Risk (9 May 2019) Is there a possibility that the Chinese government would retaliate by including the iPhone in tariffs the Chinese government places on US imports? On May 13th, it was reported that China would be raising tariffs on $60B worth of US imports, including "other telephones using cellular network or wifi". We don't see this as a meaningful risk because tariffs are levied at the port where products enter the country, and iPhones are currently produced within Chinese borders. More likely in our view is that the government could place an informal ban on purchasing certain products as it has done in the past for parts of the market (such as for government officials several years ago), which could have a negative impact on iPhone demand. Even in the absence of a formal, government issued ban, consumers may continue to protest the trade conflict by purchasing domestic branded smartphones at the expense of iPhone. What does this all mean? How do you think about bear case EPS and the near term floor for the stock? After peaking at $210 in early May, Apple shares have retreated back to the $180 range following the escalation of US/China trade rhetoric. The situation remains extremely fluid and we admit that quantifying the overall impact of geopolitical tensions on Apple is difficult given the unknowns around timing, demand impact, retaliatory measures, exclusions, etc. Near term, the greatest risk to Apple is that Chinese consumers meaningfully slow their purchases of Apple products, which would likely cause another round of estimate cuts, similar to the scenario we framed above. In the event the US places a 25% tax on all Chinese imports to the US (with no exclusions provided), and that becomes the status quo, we see 19-23% downside to FY20 EPS, and frame two scenarios in Exhibit 3 below. First, the worst case scenario where Apple absorbs all tariff costs and chooses not to pass pricing onto consumers, we'd expect our current FY20 EPS of $12.67 to fall by ~23% to $9.72. More realistic however, is that Apple will share in the incremental tariff cost with consumers (i.e. hike prices) and component suppliers or engage in other mitigation efforts, while also seeing softer US demand due to higher device prices. In this scenario, we estimate that Apple would raise the price of US devices (iPhones, iPads, Mac, Apple Watch and AirPods) by roughly 15% (Exhibit 4). As you can see in Exhibit 5 we estimate this would have a material impact on unit demand and product gross margins in the US, but that higher ASPs (from US price increases) would act as a partial offset, although we also assume the higher pricing causes US consumers to mix down to more legacy devices. Additionally, we assume Apple's Chinese device sales take a material hit as consumers switch to local Chinese brands. We expect Apple to remain aggressive on the capital allocation front and forecast a 10% dividend increase, to $0.80/quarter/share and an increase to Apple's buyback authorization of at least $50B. This would bring Apple's total buyback authorization under the plan 1652 announced a year ago to at least $150B, of which roughly $95-100B will be remaining following the March quarter, we estimate. In China, which represents roughly â…“ of total App Store gaming revenue, gaming growth inflected to +2% Y/Y from 1% declines in the December quarter. We believe that the December quarter will mark a trough for China gaming revenue growth and that growth will accelerate from the March quarter for two main reasons. First, the March quarter faced tough Y/Y comps as Chinese authorities didn't halt new gaming license approvals until March 2018, and have taken a more conservative approach to new license approvals this year. So while 959 new licenses have been approved YTD, that meaningfully trails gaming license approvals during the same period last year. Going forward however, the Y/Y gaming comps ease significantly (Exhibit 5) since nearly zero new gaming licenses were approved in the March-December 2018 period. Second, Chinese authorities just approved the first batch of 30 imported gaming licenses following a one-year suspension, with key gaming titles like Fortnite, Call of Duty Mobile and PUBG in line for approval. While the timing of these approvals is unknown, the combination of easing comps and accelerating license approvals gives us confidence China gaming revenue growth will accelerate from here, helping offset any potential slowdown in other regions. (-) Downloads growth is slowing but is being offset by growing spend per download. For the first time since at least 1Q15 (as far back as we have the data), the number of quarterly downloads declined, falling 5% Y/Y. However, net revenue per download, a gauge of consumer spend per download, increased 21% Y/Y, an acceleration from 14% Y/Y growth in the December quarter (Exhibit 6). While the decline in downloads is something investors should monitor, it's not necessarily indicative of consumer app usage trends, since App Store net revenue is correlated more so with spend per download (driven by in-app purchases) rather than the absolute level of downloads. And the acceleration in spend per download growth this quarter shows us that app engagement remains healthy. (-) Entertainment is a category to keep our eye on after a significant deceleration. Entertainment (which does not include music) is the second largest App Store category, representing ~7% of T12M App Store revenue. And while it's dwarfed by the gaming category, Entertainment has been a source of strong/emerging growth - in the last 4 years, quarterly growth averaged 104% Y/Y. In the December quarter, Entertainment net revenue growth decelerated to 39% Y/Y, from 76% Y/Y in the quarter prior. And in the March quarter, growth decelerated again to 26% Y/Y (Exhibit 7). The deceleration could be a direct result of the actions taken by some large entertainment companies that no longer support Apple's payment platform as a method of payment for new subscribers. Apple's weak C4Q iPhone results in China provided ammunition for bears to argue that Apple has lost its way in China. However, Apple Y/Y installed base share gains inflected positively in both January and February, which we believe is evidence that recent price cuts are positively stimulating demand, even in a weaker Chinese smartphone market. While it's still too early to extrapolate what this implies for March quarter iPhone shipments, recent price cuts on Apple's most popular new model in China, the XS Max (see next paragraph), combined with installed base share gains and stable iPhone builds are the most positive data points we have seen in months and makes us more confident that there is likely upside, rather than downside, to our March quarter iPhone unit estimates. And from a Services standpoint, iPhone's strong installed base share in China (Exhibit 4) increases confidence in Apple further monetizing a large, and growing user base. Contrary to expectations, the XS Max is the most popular new iPhone model with users in China. IDC data through December shows that Apple shipped 1.4M iPhone XS, 3.3M iPhone XS Max and 5.3M iPhone XR's in China in C2H18. However, active installed base data in China shows that user adoption of the iPhone XS Max is meaningfully higher than the iPhone XR, implying that while sell-in for the iPhone XR in China may have been strongest, sell-through disappointed, and sell-through for the XS Max has been healthier (Exhibit 5). This would align with our view that Chinese consumers still view the iPhone as an aspirational brand, and also helps explain why Apple (and channel partners) targeted pricing cuts on the XR earlier than the XS and XS Max. Following Apple's pre announcement on Jan. 2, the company has made clear that it plans on launching new services this year, one of which will likely be an OTT streaming service. Reports indicate that the offering will be a mix of both originally produced content and an aggregation of existing content from other streaming sources. We think the service will operate similarly to the App Store where Apple will take a 30% revenue cut. Video does reflect upside to our model; but would take 250MM subs to represent 5% of 2023 revs. In our Services Deep Dive report, we determined that Services could represent 30%+ of Apple's overall business by 2023, assuming no new Services offerings. While the streaming offering could help them reach that bogey, we are not yet convinced that streaming will meaningfully reaccelerate Services growth. If we assume that Apple charges $15 per month and takes a 30% cut from content producers, Apple would need to have 250m subscribers on its platform to represent just 5% of overall revenue by 2023. Net, we are not yet convinced that Streaming can cause an inflection in company level growth. Even with video, Services growth is not enough to offset iPhone unit declines, which should persist through 2019 and beyond. We remain cautious on iPhone demand, particularly in China, where upside looks limited this year. 2019 iPhones seem unlikely to offer compelling reasons to upgrade, and consumers may even postpone iPhone purchases until 5G. While we remain bullish on the long-term Services opportunity, it is too small to offset this material headwind for now. Investors should consider this report as only a single factor in making their investment decision. www.jpmorganmarkets.com 446 Samik Chatterjee, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-212) 622 0798                  04 February 2019 samik.x.chatterjee@jpmorgan.com Solid execution on Services; however, need to accelerate Services to offset smartphone headwinds in a more appreciable manner To date, Apple has performed better than expected on its Services opportunity, including delivering $40 bn (adjusted for recent accounting change) of revenues in FY18, which is more than 1.5x the $24 bn reported in FY16 (on old accounting) when management issued a target of doubling Services revenue by FY20. However, despite the success of the firm's Services strategy, the recently accelerating headwinds in the smartphone industry (and iPhones) are likely to drive a need for Apple to accelerate its Services offering and offset the smartphone-related headwinds in a more appreciable manner. Opportune time to use strong balance sheet to re-focus on Services theme In recent times, headwinds in the smartphone industry, including a challenging outlook for iPhone volumes in both calendar 2018 and 2019, has diluted investorsâ€™ focus on the Services opportunity for Apple and riveted investors to iPhone volume fluctuations. Given the broader sell-off in the markets and with most technology companies trading below their recent 52-week highs, we believe valuations for technology companies are more digestible currently relative to mid-2018 and would argue that it is an opportune time for Apple to leverage its strong balance sheet to further consolidate its ecosystem. Apple ended the most recent quarter with $130 bn of cash on the balance sheet and generates roughly $45 bn of free cash flow after dividends annually, which effectively puts ~$175 bn at its disposal without having to end a fiscal year with an increased debt position (in line with its long-term target of being cash neutral). Use of $175 bn can buy a lot of growth, although Apple does not have a history of large acquisitions As shown in Table 1, Apple has a history of making multiple â€œbolt-onâ€ acquisitions every year, which have largely been focused on bringing hardware technology that the company expects to be crucial to competitive differentiation in-house and better manage its development toward commercialization. In fact, Apple has been very successful with the strategy to-date as many of the applications in use on iPhones today can be associated with bolt-on technology acquisitions of the past (e.g., 3D sensing facial recognition, Siri speech recognition). Despite a track record of multiple acquisitions, the largest acquisition to date for Apple remains Beats Electronics, which was acquired for proceeds of $3 bn, while typical acquisition sizes are in the hundreds of millions. Apple's track record on acquisitions has made a lot of investors question the willingness of the current management team to explore large acquisitions. 2 447 Samik Chatterjee, CFA However, Apple has been open to changing strategic direction in the past Contrary to popular investor opinion, which questions Appleâ€™s willingness to explore opportunities outside its traditional strategy, it is worth underscoring the acquisition of Beats Electronics represented a significant change in strategy. In addition to the $3 bn purchase price, which was significantly higher than the typical acquisition price, the Beats Electronics acquisition highlighted Apple's appetite for acquiring Service businesses to stimulate growth (e.g., Beats Music) as it aimed to revitalize its floundering music business, that was largely predicated on iTunes, which was facing stiff competition from streaming services, such as Spotify and Pandora. A year after acquiring Beats Music, Apple successfully launched a rebranded music and video streaming service, Apple Music, which has since grown its paid subscriber base at a +70% CAGR to more than ~50 mn by end of FY18. By comparison, Appleâ€™s largest competitor, Spotify (covered by JPM Internet analyst, Doug Anmuth), boasts ~90 mn paid subscribers (revenue of ~$5 bn), which has grown at a +50% CAGR over a similar time period. Interestingly, with the acquisition of Beats Electronics, Apple also showed a change in strategy by illustrating a willingness to maintain the Beats brand image as it relates to its product portfolio of premium headphones and earbuds, which have also been successful to date. To that end, examples of Service businesses that we believe best fit with Appleâ€™s strategy include media content delivery platforms, such as Netflix, and gaming platforms, such as Activision and Zynga. Even hardware acquisitions could prove synergistic to certain Services offerings As we look at the importance of the Services opportunity for the company, the popular investor perception seems to be that subscription-based software acquisitions represents the greatest strategic priority. However, we do not rule out the possibility of hardware product acquisitions that could drive synergies with certain services offerings and drive accelerated pace of growth. Examples of hardware-based businesses include home platforms, such as Sonos, and health platforms, such as Peloton. 3 448 Samik Chatterjee, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-212) 622 0798                  04 February 2019 samik.x.chatterjee@jpmorgan.com The following section takes a closer look at some of the specific examples we discussed on page 1 and the potential impact on Appleâ€™s business drivers. Video Gaming The gaming industry could fit strategically in terms of services offering and provide leverage to an industry rapidly moving to the mobile platform The video gaming industry is in the midst of a physical to digital game transition with consumers increasingly purchasing content and services digitally and engaging with live services including micro-transactions, downloadable content, subscriptions, and Esports. NewZoo estimates that 2.3 bn gamers globally will spend roughly $135 bn in 2018, including slightly less than half of the spend being on mobile platforms. Additionally, within mobile platforms, 80% of the spend is expected on smartphones, while the remaining comes from a variety of devices including tablets. Looking forward, continuing on the broader trend of growth above the industry, NewZoo expects mobile gaming to grow at a strong CAGR of +13% over the next few years, outperforming the overall gaming industry growth at +9% CAGR. Figure 1: Global Games Market vs. Global Mobile Games Market $ in Billions $200 $174                     2018     2021 $150             $135 $100                                                $90 $63 $50 $0 Games Market          Mobile Games Market Source: Newzoo. High-end gaming could drive a smartphone replacement cycle and support the iPhone premium through leadership in compute/graphics capabilities Similar to the experience with the PC market, where gaming as a use case continues to drive a certain section of consumers to look for continuous hardware upgrades, we believe the increasing utilization of mobile devices for gaming can drive a replacement cycle for smartphones. For example, consumers engaged in competitive high-end gaming look for the latest compute and graphics capabilities, which can not only help drive a replacement cycle for iPhones with every launch, but could further support the premium for iPhones if Apple can maintain a leadership in terms of compute/graphics capabilities. Gaming could fit strategically into Apple's AR/VR leadership Gaming should offer synergies with Apple's iPhone hardware given well-established leadership that Apple has shown relative to 3D sensing, which would be a key enabler for augmented reality and virtual reality applications. We expect adoption of world-facing 3D sensing on iPhones in 2020, which should stimulate growth in AR/VR applications for smartphones, including on the gaming front. 4 449

Apple guided to F2Q19 revenue in the range of $55-$59 bn for F2Q (vs. JPMe of $56.7 bn and consensus of $59.0 bn heading into the announcement), which includes $1.3 bn negative FX impact. Despite the in-line revenue guidance, gross margin outlook was modestly disappointing (range of 37.0%-38.0% vs. JPMe and consensus of 38.0% heading into the announcement), although explained largely by loss of leverage on lower volumes as well as a headwind of -90 bps y/y and -60 bps q/q from unfavorable FX. As we look to the remainder of the year, we believe the combination of moderating FX headwinds (were currencies to hold at current levels) and increasing memory price tailwinds are likely to help drive a sequential improvement in gross margins from F2Q19 levels. ï‚· Services momentum continued, helped by growth in installed base of devices. Services revenue was $10,875 mn in F1Q19 (vs. JPMe of $10,761 mn), implying growth of +19% y/y, led by strength from the App Store, Apple Pay, Cloud Services (+40% y/y), Apple Care, App Store Search Ad business and Apple Music (50 mn+ paid subscribers). The strong Services revenue growth included paid subscriptions of 360 mn in F1Q19 (vs. 330 mn in F4Q and 240 mn a year ago) and the company now expects paid subscriptions to exceed 500 mn during 2020, placing it well on track of reaching its target Services revenue by FY20 ($50 bn adjusted for accounting changes). However, at the same time Apple highlighted certain factors driving a modest deceleration in Services growth trends, relative to the strength in recent quarters, including: 1) FX impact: 60% of services revenue is derived outside U.S, thereby negatively impacted by strengthening of US dollar; 2) App Store in China: the issue of approval of new gaming titles in China was a headwind in F1Q19; and 3) Deceleration in Apple Care as it laps a year of strong performance in 2018. ï‚· Services opportunity to be driven by installed base growth and broadening content portfolio. Relative to the drivers of the Services opportunity for the company, management highlighted high-single digit growth in the installed base, which rose to 1.4 bn devices relative to 1.3 bn at end of FY17, and included 900 mn iPhones (which rose +75 mn y/y). The other primary driver of Services growth includes a broader services portfolio, as demonstrated with strong growth in recent service launches including Apple Pay and Apple Music. Additionally, Apple briefly spoke to its intent of providing original video content as well as acceleration in third- party video subscriptions to fully leverage its installed base of Apple TV devices as well as Airplay to fully leverage service opportunities on third-party hardware. ï‚· Lowering estimates largely on softer gross margin estimates and higher operating expenses. We are modestly trimming our full-year estimates for FY19E, FY20E, and FY21E to account for lower gross margins (led by loss of volume leverage and higher promotions) and higher operating expenses relative to our expectations. Our December-19 price target of $228 is unchanged, with a higher target multiple on account of greater contribution to earnings from the Services group valued at a higher multiple in the SOTP-based valuation, offsetting the impact of the lower earnings forecast. 2 520
