We estimate that services annual revenue per device currently stands at ~$30, up from $25/device just two years ago. However, this metric underestimates the long-term revenue potential for a number of reasons. First, the majority of Apple users don't yet pay for services, suggesting that revenue per "active" user is well above, and possibly double, the $30 level. Second, services revenue is growing Y/Y for every customer cohort and in every region, suggesting that at maturity revenue per device could approach $100 or more (Exhibit 20). We don't view this as a stretch given Amazon Prime has 106M users paying $99/year and Netflix has 111M paid subs spending $120/year. Third, Apple disclosed last quarter that they have 240M paid subscriptions across their Services offerings, equivalent to 18% of the total device installed base, leaving much room for improved recurring revenue. ...and shows no sign of slowing given lots of low hanging fruit. We see a number of levers Apple can pull to accelerate services monetization: 1) Apple Music: Paid subscribers grew 80% in 2017, slightly faster than peers, with penetration of just 2.9% of total Apple devices (Exhibit 31). 2) iCloud: Subscribers are growing even faster than Apple Music and two recently announced data center launches in China, one of which went live February 28, should meaningfully improve the user experience and drive increasing user penetration in coming quarters (Exhibit 30). 3) Apple Pay: Now works in 50% of all US retail locations, but usage remains low and that's likely to change as consumers become more comfortable with mobile wallet technology and international markets catch-up to the US (Exhibit 32 & Exhibit 34). 4) App Store: Broadening payment options can accelerate demand. The introduction of WeChat Pay and AliPay as methods of payment on the App Store coincided with accelerating App Store growth in 2017 (Exhibit 22), and China is now both the largest and one of the fastest growing app store regions globally. Yet, in some other countries, such as Brazil, Apple still requires payment via credit cards, which we expect to change in the future. 5) Subscription Churn: Apple recently added team members with experience managing subscription businesses, and as a result, user churn declined meaningfully in the December quarter, accelerating subscriber and overall services revenue growth (Exhibit 19). 6) New offerings like original content and AR-centric apps on the App Store are easy wins that can both convert new users and increase spend of existing services users as new content is added to the platform. With a stronger and more consistent source of EPS growth, we have increasing confidence in multiple expansion. In fact, a sum of the parts analysis that credits Apple's hardware business with a multiple that blends HPQ and 4192 MSFT and Apple's services business with the average of consumer platform peers (Exhibit 6) provides additional support for our $203 PT, translating to a 14.5x P/E or half a turn higher than our previous view on slightly lower EPS. Services metrics worth monitoring: Device installed base growth, Apple Services paid subscribers, payments to the developer community/App Store revenue, apps available on iOS, app downloads, Apple Music subscribers, Apple Pay country availability, # of contactless-ready Apple Pay locations (Exhibit 24 - Exhibit 34). 4203 Framing Our Scenario Analysis Why we think investors should prioritize their time on Apple Services. Over the past 5 years, Apple investors have primarily focused their time and attention on the burgeoning importance of the iPhone. And rightfully so, given the product now contributes 62% of total company revenue, and grew at a 12% CAGR over the last 5 years. However, as smartphone replacement cycles extend and growth slows with lower carrier subsidies, higher quality devices, and maturing penetration, the period of outsized device growth is likely behind us. As a result, we believe that investors need to shift focus to Apple's Services business to better understand the company's ability to grow revenue long-term. Why? Because we see a scenario where replacement cycles extend further, device installed base growth slows to single digits (from 14% over the last 2 years) and Apple still generates low-to-mid single digit revenue growth. How? Increasing services monetization, which we see as the key priority for Apple going forward. With close to $200 billion in excess cash and FCF available to use over the next 12 months, Apple can support the stock as the investment thesis evolves from one of product cycle- to services-led growth. In our base case, we assume that replacement cycles continue to extend towards 4.5 years, implying an iPhone replacement cycle close to 4 years, as Apple total device shipments decline 50bps annually and device installed base grows mid-single digits, with ASPs flat as Apple continues to innovate on the device side and drive users towards newer technologies. We view our unit assumptions as rather conservative given smartphone replacement cycles are approaching PC replacement cycles today, a device that arguably isn't as mobile and is used less frequently. Additionally, services revenue per device growth stays flat with 2018 at 7.7% as some of the low hanging fruit we discuss, like iCloud in China, expansion of original content and a greater diversity of payment forms comes to fruition. In this scenario, Apple revenue would grow at 5% every year through 2024, implying that only slight device declines coupled with a flatline in services revenue per user growth (despite the low hanging fruit that should otherwise accelerate spend) would be enough to keep Apple's revenue trajectory modestly positive. Importantly, we believe this analysis could prove to be conservative given it implies no new product category launches, no stabilization in the handset replacement cycle in the next 5 years and a significant slowdown in installed base growth from the last 2 years. Services growth accelerated to 27% normalized growth in December from 25% in September and 21% a year ago. Services is becoming an even more important element of the Apple story, contributing over 30% of gross profit by the end of 2021 allowing for total company revenue and EPS growth even without device revenue growth beyond FY19. In practicality, we expect the company to earmark a modest portion of the $163B of net cash to acquisitions ($4B is Apple's record year of acquisition spend) and return the rest to shareholders through buybacks and dividends, likely during a multi-year period. Press reports around lower supply chain orders in the March and June quarters largely noise, but we now contemplate price elasticity later in the cycle. We believe the majority of noise around supply chain "cuts" tie to the faster than expected ramp of iPhone production in the December quarter (pull-in from March) and inventory disparities across the supply chain that are typically corrected once products are fully ramped. However, there is also an argument that as new products mature and more demand comes from late adopters, Apple could see a shift away from higher priced, new SKUs toward recently discounted older SKUs like iPhone 7 and iPhone 6 which was re-introduced in China last year. Our lower FY18 estimates contemplate this dynamic as well as recently reduced battery replacement prices ($29 vs. $79 previously for iPhone 6 and older) and news flow around a broader line-up of iPhone X-like products, including larger screen and cheaper versions, both of which could push some upgrade demand into FY19. Additionally, 3rd party industry reports recently highlighted that the iPhone 7 Plus and iPhone 7 were the #2 and #5, respectively, best-selling smartphones in China in 2017, despite their seemingly iterative updates from the iPhone 6s. We believe the primary drivers of demand for the iPhone 7 and 7 Plus are the aging iPhone 6 installed base and lower price points, which were discounted by 10-15% last September following Appleâ€™s most recent iPhone launch. First, Apple was able to build 7-8M more iPhone X units that we originally thought for December and that pulls in production from the March quarter. Secondly, some iPhone suppliers without yield issues built signficant component inventory in December, causing weaker orders to those suppliers in the March quarter. We believe recent supply chain data points are explained by timing and that the December + March quarter production plans are relatively unchanged from two months ago. Our view that iPhone demand is intact is supported by Hon Hai's recent December month revenue beat of 48% (see report here). Furthermore, Apple typically beats the supply chain builds by 18%, on average, over the past five years suggesting reported iPhone units could be meaningfully higher than 64M (Exhibit 9). China smartphone data also highlights pent-up demand and switching opportunity for iPhone. We believe Chinese consumers are especially sensitive to new technology and form factor changes. This is the first time Apple stretched a form factor three years, creating pent-up demand, especially in China. The Jiguang data confirms this dynamic, as over 75% of the active iPhone base is two generations or older (Exhibit 7). For comparison, our recent US smartphone survey pointed to 63% of respondents owning a 2+ year old iPhone in the US. Additionally, we see the largest cohort of iPhone upgraders to the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus in the 4 weeks through October 22nd have upgraded from the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus (Exhibit 8), which further highlights the pent up demand in China. The Jigaung data also highlights that in the 4 weeks ending October 22nd, more "switchers" left their Chinese branded smartphone for an iPhone than iPhone users left for a Chinese branded smartphone, across all local vendors (Exhibit 9). In fact, Apple's net switching rate, or the net amount of switchers gained/lost as a percentage of all brand switchers increased to 7.6% in the latest 4 week period, up from 6.7% in the prior 4 week period ending October 8th. Comparatively, Vivo was the only Chinese smartphone vendor to gain "net switchers", albeit at a significantly lower rate (Exhibit 10). We expect this trend to only accelerate as future data sets will include the period after the iPhone X first began shipping. Mix of larger display iPhone models continues to increase; positive for ASP growth. Over the last 12 months, the mix of Plus model iPhone shipments in China rose (Exhibit 11) as consumer preferences shifted to larger displays and Apple's iPhone portfolio re-oriented to plus-sized models. This is an important driver of ASP growth, especially considering this year's Plus models are priced, on average, 19% higher than their smaller model counterpart. This trend is borne out in the Jiguang data as well, with the mix of "Plus" models as a % of the active iPhone base in China increasing 600bps YTD, to 40.4% (Exhibit 12). With reports of stronger demand for the iPhone 8 Plus vs. the iPhone 8 (IT Hardware: What We Learned in Asia), the continued rollout of the iPhone X, and purchase intentions in China that are much more skewed to the iPhone 8 Plus and X vs. the iPhone 8 (Exhibit 13), we expect meaningful uplift to iPhone ASPs in FY18 and forecast a 22% Y/Y increase in ASPs to $796. Growth in the active smartphone base in China supports strong Apple Services growth. According to data from Sensor Tower, Apple's App Store generated over $4B in revenue from China YTD, which we largely attribute to growth of the active iPhone user base in China. In fact, plotting monthly App Store revenue in China with Jiguang iPhone market share data through the first 9 months of this year points to a correlation of 0.82 with an r-squared of 0.67 (Exhibit 14). To the extent we see an acceleration in smartphone market share gains, we would expect App Store revenue growth in China to accelerate, potentially boosted further by new Augmented Reality applications. Bringing it all together: We remain very bullish on Apple's prospects in China. Even after recent smartphone user base share gains, we believe that Apple is just turning the corner in China and growth will meaningfully accelerate in the quarters to come (Exhibit 15), due to a litany of factors such as 1) easier 6712 compares, 2) pent up demand for a revolutionary new iPhone, 3) a meaningfully larger base of aged iPhones ripe for an upgrade, 4) non-Apple smartphone owners that have already begun switching to iPhone, 5) growth in iPhone ASPs from positive mix shift and 6) growth of the overall Apple ecosystem in China that will continue to drive higher services revenue. If we are correct, then we believe China could grow over 70% and account for 25% of Apple revenue in FY18, similar to the last iPhone supercycle in FY15 (and up from 20% in FY17). According to our April 2017 AlphaWise US Smartphone survey, Ninety-two percent of US iPhone users who plan to upgrade their phone in the next year plan to repurchase an iPhone, up from 86% the year before (Exhibit 8). Apple also enjoys higher repurchase rates in international markets with an average loyalty rate of 86% compared to 61% for Samsung in those markets. We believe Apple's early lead in Augmented Reality will only push customer loyalty rates higher in coming years. What's more, a weaker US Dollar compared to several international currencies, including Euro (+6% Y/Y), Brazilian Real (+6% Y/Y), Indian Rupee (+4% Y/Y), and Chinese Yuan (+2% Y/Y), helps offset the recent USD price increases in these markets. Slow manufacturing ramp and potential yield constraints on iPhone X push units into the March quarter. The November 3 iPhone X launch date is later than past iPhones, likely a function of a slower manufacturing ramp as the supply chain works to improve yields on new components. To account for a more back- end loaded production ramp in the December quarter, we shift 2M iPhone X units from the December to the March quarter, potentially setting up a seasonally better (less weak) March (Exhibit 10). Net, our December and March quarter shipments of 81M (+3% Y/Y) and 71M (+40% Y/Y), respectively (vs. 83M and 69M prior), translate to unchanged FY18 iPhone shipments of 262M (Exhibit 9), 6% above the current consensus estimate of 247M. China remains a key driver of our above consensus estimates, where the number of iPhones due to be upgraded grew 56% this year setting up for a powerful upgrade cycle (Exhibit 11). Higher ASPs translate to FY18 EPS of $12.60, 15% above consensus; PT to $194 (from $182). In addition to our higher ASP assumptions across iPhone, iPad, Watch, and AppleCare, we raise our FY18 forecast for Apple Watch to 25M units (+39% Y/Y) to reflect our bullish outlook on the Apple Watch Series 3, particularly the cellular enabled model. However, we also lower FY18 gross margins across the device segments to account for further memory market tightness, driving our FY18 company gross margin to 38.3% (down 10bps Y/Y), from 38.6% prior. Together, these changes drive our FY18 revenue and EPS to $301B (from $288B) and $12.60 (from $11.80), 14-15% above current Street estimates, and our price target to $194 (from $182). With our FY18 revenue and EPS estimates meaningfully ahead of consensus and shares trading at 12.6x, compared to the iPhone 6 cycle peak multiple of 15.4x, we continue to believe that a period of accelerated growth as smartphone users upgrade/switch to the first new iPhone form factor in three years is not priced into shares. Apple shares are up 50% YTD compared to the last two upgrade cycles - iPhone 4 and iPhone 6 - when shares rose an average of 142% over the cycle (Exhibit 12). We continue to see bull case valuation of $253 in a scenario of strong consumer adoption of augmented reality apps that extends the iPhone upgrade cycle into FY19 with accelerating services revenue growth in FY19-20 (Global Technology: Can Augmented Reality Drive the Next Big Smartphone Upgrade Cycle?). 84 2 Analysis Exhibit 1: An equal-weighted portfolio of Apple products shows hardware pricing up 1-3% vs. period prior to last week's product event, although actual shipment mix leads to even greater ASP uplift Apple Products: New vs. Old Pricing                                                                        Post-Launch Pricing Pre-Launch Pricing $-                       $200                       $400                      $600            $800 $692 iPhone                                                                                                      $673            +3% $689 iPad                                                                                                                    +2% $672 $326 Apple Watch                                                                          +2% $319 $176 Apple TV                                                   +1% $174 AppleCare for                                   $149 +16% iPhone*                                      $129 Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research; *AppleCare for iPhone 8 and 8 Plus will be priced at $149, and at $199 for the iPhone X. Apple reduced iPhone channel inventory by 3.3M, more than 2x the three-year June quarter average, which represents an incremental $1.4B, or 3%. Even with the channel inventory headwind, revenue growth accelerated to 7%, from 5% in the prior quarter, and grew across all key product categories - iPhone (+3%), iPad (+2%), Mac (+7%), Services (+22%) and Other (+23%; includes Watch, AirPods and accessories). iPhone Supercycle on track for a fall launch. Despite investor concerns that OLED iPhone shipments could push to Nov/Dec or even next year, management guided September quarter bullishly and sounded confident on upcoming product launches this fall. We increase our September quarter iPhone unit shipment estimate by 6M to 43M units, in part due to higher overall demand but also due to some of the new products likely contributing later in the quarter. Gross margin story intact despite rising component costs. The combination of leverage on higher revenues, increasing services mix (16% of total revenue, highest quarterly total ever), and increasing services margin offset higher memory costs in the June quarter. Heading into the fall iPhone launch, we're increasingly convinced Apple can pass on higher component costs associated with new technologies making our 80bps iPhone GM decline in FY18 look conservative. All else equal, a flat iPhone GM adds $0.22 to our $11.80 FY18 EPS forecast. China recovery supports supercycle thesis. The number of aged iPhones in China that are due for an upgrade grew 56% this year setting up for accelerating upgrades when a new iPhone form factor launches this fall. What's more, the switching opportunity is ripe in China. Roughly one-third of Chinese smartphone brand users (Vivo, Oppo) intend to consider an iPhone upon upgrade while only twenty percent are loyal to their existing provider. The combination of these factors drive our 66% bottom up China iPhone unit growth forecast in FY18. Revenue in mainland China grew 6% at constant currency in June and while Greater China revenue declined 10% as reported (less at constant currency), it was a modest improvement from -13% in the first half of the year. Although Apple has been aggressive relative to other royalty negotiators, we believe Qualcomm would hurt themselves more than they would help with Draconian measures like an ITC trade injunction against Apple. Not only would this likely push Apple further into the arms of Intel for baseband chips but it would deprive Qualcomm of chip revenues for lost iPhone sales in the US. Outside of the US market similar trade aggression is also possible but the negative outcomes for Qualcomm are equally self destructive in our opinion. This is not to say that such measures are impossible but we believe they are relatively improbable at this stage in the negotiations. To put numbers to Qualcommâ€™s chip exposure to Apple we estimate annual revenue exposure this coming fiscal year from the Decâ€™17 QTR to the Septâ€™18 QTR to be ~$1.3bn or 6% of Qualcommâ€™s total revenue. We calculate that this represents a relatively small 3% of total EBT for Qualcomm. However, we would also note that Apple volumes are a large chunk of TSMC capacity utilization for Qualcomm. Losing those volumes would likely have both short and long term impacts on QCOMâ€™s economics at TSMC in our opinion. Net, our more bullish iPhone unit and ASP outlook drives FY18 revenue and EPS 12% above current consensus and pushes our PT to $161 (from $154) based on the same 14x P/E which is around where shares peaked during the iPhone 6 cycle. Steady supply chain and demand data points clear path to supercycle. Current iPhone production forecast, as published by Morgan Stanley's Greater China Hardware team, reflects C1H17 29% below C2H16, which is better than prior year trend of -34% H/H. We believe this is a function of Apple managing tight iPhone channel inventory ahead of a major high-end form factor change. Morgan Stanley's AlphaWise tracker, which compiles sell-through data using web search analysis, indicates 60M unit demand for the March quarter. Historically, our Tracker has been accurate directionally, though we think the magnitude of the iPhone demand upside this quarter is likely overstated, and attribute some of the upside to elevated search interest in anticipation of the 10th anniversary iPhone launch. Net, we maintain our 51M March quarter iPhone forecast, roughly in-line with consensus, raise March Q ASP 2% to $675, and see the company reporting revenue at the upper end of the $51.5B to $53.5B range (our new estimate is $52.9B, up from $52.2B). We continue to expect a 38.9% gross margin, at the upper end of 38-39% guidance range, and EPS of $2.03, in line with consensus. Expect typically conservative June quarter guidance. We model June quarter iPhone units declining 22% Q/Q, slightly more than last year to reflect potential for delayed purchases ahead of the September iPhone launch. As is typical, with the exception of the last two quarters of strong guides post a period of channel inventory correction, we expect the June quarter revenue guidance mid-point to come in below current consensus. We currently model $43.2B June Q revenue, below consensus of $45.6B. Our June EPS of $1.45 is also below consensus of $1.62. We lower June quarter gross margin by 70 bps, to 37.8%, to better reflect higher memory costs, and we view company commentary around how much higher commodity costs will impact margins as the main guidance wild card. We view 37.5-38% as the gross margin guidance bogey to keep the stock on its upward trajectory as buy-side expectations seem to be lower than the sell-side consensus of 38.3% in June. However, we do note Apple appears to have pre- purchased more components this year, as we highlighted from the last 10Q filing, which should help minimize memory headwinds relative to competitors. At the end of the day, we don't expect June quarter guidance to be meaningfully more conservative than in the past (on average, revenue guide is 2% lower, gross margin 30bps lower than consensus) and weakness the quarter prior to a major form factor change is to be expected. We expect Apple to increase its dividend and stock buybacks along with earnings. Long term, we see Apple returning its fully taxed FCF assuming existing tax policies globally. Based on this philosophy and historical trends, we model a 10% increase in dividends per share to $0.64. We further model $30B of stock buybacks over the next year. This means Apple will likely raise cumulative buyback authorization from $175B to at least $210B. We see potential for higher cash return, mainly through buybacks, as we gain clarity on cash repatriation, which could add $0.60 to EPS annually. A lower tax rate could add another $1.00-1.50 in our estimation. Building upon our Global upgrade analysis, we have created an interactive model that allows investors to adjust the assumptions we use in both our top down and 24 2 bottom up analyses, across the six geographic regions as defined by IDC, to come to their own iPhone unit conclusions. In our top down analysis, key variables that can be adjusted are; length of replacement cycle, iPhone retention rate and the ratio of shipments as a % of estimated upgraders. We have two versions of our bottoms up analysis - one that allows you to adjust replacement cycle length, iPhone retention rate and the switching rate for all other brands, and one that is more detailed and allows you to adjust replacement cycle length, iPhone retention rate and the switching rate for each of the largest vendors (as well as all smaller vendors collectively). This Morgan Stanley Interactive iPhone Upgrade Model is available upon request. 25 3

Investors should consider this report as only a single factor in making their investment decision. www.jpmorganmarkets.com 155 Rod Hall, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-415) 315-6713          14 February 2017 rod.b.hall@jpmorgan.com 3D sensor technology overview 3D sensing from a basic hardware point of view is relatively straightforward. A light source bounces off of the object to be scanned and is then detected by a light sensor. To scan in 3D the sensor needs to measure the time of flight of the light as well as the image itself. With all of that data, complex processing algorithms are used to render a 3D â€œimageâ€ that can then be used for facial recognition as well as other applications. In this section we provide more detail on these functions. 1. Light Source: The light emitter (laser diode or infrared LED) emits from the light source toward a target object, while the object reflects the light (photons) back to the image sensor. In the case of the new iPhone sensor we believe this source is an array of semiconductor lasers called VCSELs (Vertical Cavity Surface Emitting Laser, pronounced â€œvixelâ€). It is also worth noting that these VCSELs emit light in a specific infrared frequency. 2. Light Filter: To obtain a noise-free scan, a filter is used to eliminate any light not at the specific frequency being emitted. This filter must eliminate stray light noise from all angles, which is harder to do than it sounds given prismatic effects, etc. 3. Image Sensor: The image sensor then determines when the light arrives and at what intensity level. Arrival time or â€œtime of flightâ€ provides the 3D depth information. For the purposes of a pure 3D scan returning a surface shape the intensity information is not technically needed but might be used to otherwise enhance the processed image. 4. Processor IC: The processor IC executes sophisticated algorithms to decipher the received patterns and produces a VGA size depth image of the scene. This depth image can then be compared to a stored facial scan like a fingerprint or, eventually, used for other applications. 2 156 Rod Hall, CFA                            North America Equity Research (1-415) 315-6713                         14 February 2017 rod.b.hall@jpmorgan.com Figure 1: PrimeSense 3D sensing technology Source: PrimeSense. Known technology challenges The following is a summary of technology challenges we believe exist based on our discussions with contacts. ï‚· Ambient or background illumination (noise)â€”Ambient light (such as sunlight) may provide uncorrelated photons. Specialized filter technology can be employed to partially eliminate this, though some stray light in the specific infrared frequency being used is always a possibility. ï‚· Optical crosstalk from cover glass/plasticâ€”The devicesâ€™ cover glass/plastic may lead to optical crosstalk (noise). This makes the sensor always receive two targetsâ€”one reflection from the 3D object and one from the cover glass/plastic. We believe specialized filter coatings are required to eliminate/minimize this. ï‚· VCSEL array manufacturingâ€”Unlike single-point VCSELs, we understand that the light source for this sensor package is a 10x10 array of 100 individual VCSELs and is possibly larger. This is a first as we understand it and materially increases the yield difficulty for manufacturing, in our opinion. We believe this makes the playing field relatively level for LITE vs. IIVI, though we believe IIVIâ€™s in-house EPI makes its spin-up even more challenging. ï‚· Processingâ€”Processing the data off of the sensor is a challenging computational task, in which we believe Primesense/Apple has a material IP advantage. Looking forward, this could manifest itself as a key competitive advantage for Apple. 3 157

The higher-priced Plus is more popular than 5181 before, and so is Jet Black, which is only available in the two higher memory capacity configurations. Some suppliers remain conservative on component bottlenecks for the Plus leading to our Asia Tech team's 73M build estimate for the quarter, up from 72M previously. iPhone upside is slightly offset by iPads, where we lowered shipments from 15M to 11M. In total, we estimate revenue of $74.8B, close to a year ago, but GM of 38.5%, 160bps lower Y/Y due to the more costly 7 Plus, resulting in EPS of $3.19. Our estimates are close to consensus, except GM where we are 50bps lower. We expect guidance close to or modestly above $75B at the mid-point, while GM guidance could be lower than consensus of 39%, which was the case in each of the last four quarters. Near-term outperformance helps but the real catalyst is the FY18 supercycle. AAPL shares have priced in positive estimate revisions for the 7 cycle, which is warranted given the slew of positive demand and supply chain data points. Our Asia Tech team recently raised Dec Q iPhone builds by 1M, while other data points suggest even larger revisions. For example, Dialog's (covered by Francois Meunier) Sep Q upside translates into 11M or more iPhones. Importantly, we do not believe shares price in the FY18 supercycle. With an iPhone installed base that is 60% larger but unit estimates just 6% higher as compared to iPhone 6, we see potential for meaningfully positive FY18 estimate revisions. We believe accelerating iPhone growth could drive AAPL towards our bull case of $162 based on FY18 EPS of $11 and a 15x multiple, which is more in-line with where the stock peaked during the iPhone 6 supercycle. 5192

We think Apple has over 600M iPhone users today. We conservatively assume 30% of iPhones are sold to new users - Apple has been tracking ahead of that in recent quarters - which accounts for 66M of the 219M iPhones we model for FY17. So only 25% of the current installed base needs to refresh for Apple to sell the remaining 153M iPhones. We think that is quite reasonable, as it implies a four-year iPhone life, and our global consumer survey in June revealed that about half of iPhone users still have 4" versions (5, 5s, 5c, SE). While some will upgrade to the SE, many will pick a larger iPhone in our view. A stronger iPhone 7 cycle would build investor confidence and expand the multiple heading into the FY18 supercycle. We see several tailwinds that present an attractive risk-reward near-term. Investor expectations were low coming into the iPhone 7 cycle, with many questioning whether negative iPhone growth was possible in FY17. Yet, we see stronger US carrier pre-orders as evidence iPhone 6 users are beginning to upgrade, Samsung Note recall may be driving share to Apple at the high-end, and more aggressive carrier promotions can help offset purchasing delays ahead of an OLED-based iPhone next year. Importantly, we see an iPhone supercycle next year driven by a 60% larger user base compared to when iPhone 6 launched, a new full-screen, slimmer form factor, and meaningfully longer battery life and wireless charging as key drivers. As evidence of a more meaningful product cycle unfolds over the next 2-3 quarters, we see Street estimates moving higher. We maintain our $123 price target, which is 14x FY17e EPS of $8.80 or 12x FY18e EPS of $10.20. Morgan estimates. 2 71 Rod Hall, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-415) 315-6713          27 July 2016 rod.b.hall@jpmorgan.com Positives Better iPhone sell-through iPhone sell-through in FQ3 was ~44m, ~7% or 3m units above our estimate. Management commented that the number of switchers from Android continues to be strong and that iPhone SE demand outpaced supply during the quarter. We believe that better sell-through reads across slightly positively to the broader macro spending situation though we note that overall market number and Appleâ€™s own numbers remain weak with iPhone revenue down 23% Y/Y. Android switchers Tim Cook said that the company has added â€œmillions of first-time smartphone buyersâ€ in the June quarter and switchers accounted for the highest percentage of quarterly iPhone sales the company ever measured. We believe that strong adoption of smaller screen iPhones is likely helping the percentages here. Heading into CQ2, our estimate of the switching rate was <0.5% and we believe that the company ended up with a roughly ~1% Android switching rate. In absolute terms, Apple said that YTD iPhone sales to switchers are the greatest the company has ever seen in any nine-month period and that its active user base grew double digits Y/Y. We estimate that the iPhone installed base grew by ~28% Y/Y. to ~900m+ users. iPad bounces back iPad shipments in FQ3 at 10m units were 11% above our estimate and iPad ASP at $490 was 18% above our estimate, we believe due to strong sales of the iPad Pro. We believe that the iPad ASP may come off of the strong FQ3 levels as the mix of iPad Pros gives way in the back to school season to less expensive models. Solid margins despite iPhone ASP drop and inventory reduction Non-GAAP Gross Margin in FQ3 was 38.5% or 0.3pp above our estimate and GAAP Gross Margin at 38% was at the high end of the companyâ€™s guidance range (37.5%-38%). We note the strong margin performance in light of weaker than expected iPhone ASP during the quarter and believe it highlights strong execution on supply chain cost control by Apple as well as the ability of the brand to retain value even in the midst of weaker demand. Guidance beat The mid-point of Appleâ€™s FQ4 revenue guidance at $46.5bn (range: $45.5bn- $47.5bn) was 2% above consensus and ~4% above our estimate. We believe that continued strength in the iPhone SE combined with better than expected end market demand is driving better revenue guidance for FQ4. iPhone SE shipments solid Apple noted on the call that iPhone SE demand outstripped supply in both emerging and developed markets over the quarter. We estimate that there were ~10m SE units shipped, assuming an ASP of $450. Note that we are also implicitly assuming minimal price discounting of iPhones that were cleared from inventory during the quarter. 3 72

The fact that Apple does not use 46% of its offshore (ASI) earnings for tax reporting purposes is what we believe throws most people off in attempts to calculate the effective underlying tax rate. For illustration â€“ Appleâ€™s reported EBT in FY15 was $72.6bn, including ~$47.6bn of foreign earnings. We believe that due to FASBâ€™s accounting requirements, Apple accounted for US tax on just 54% of these foreign earnings and then deferred the tax given the intent to leave the earnings offshore. Subtracting the EBT not reported for tax calculation leaves us with ~$50.8bn of taxable EBT from a GAAP accounting standpoint. On the tax paid/accounted for side of the equation Appleâ€™s reported tax of $19.1bn in FY15 includes ~$1.4bn of deferred taxes. Adjusting for this we calculate reported tax paid of ~$17.7bn â€“ an effective P&L tax rate of 34.9% on EBT of ~$50.8bn. No change in macroeconomic and currency-related risk factors. Despite management spending more than the usual amount of time on macro headwinds during the recent earnings call, there were no new disclosures in the latest 10-Q. We looked back at Apple's filings in 2009 and 2013 when the stock had ~50% corrections, and found no additional risk factors compared to the current 10-Q. The exception was a disclosure in 2009 that noted Apple had only one wireless provider in some countries, which is no longer the case. We also compared 2013 filings to earlier ones, and found a few interesting new disclosures: (1) gross margins will be lower in FY13, (2) Apple makes prepayments to or invests in certain suppliers and if these suppliers experience financial problems Apple's investment may be devalued, and (3) litigation may be expensive, time-consuming, disruptive to operations and distracting to management. New disclosures in 2009 filings compared to previous ones include: (1) the financial crisis could impact Apple's business and stock price, (2) margins may decrease from FY08 levels, (3) Steve Jobs was taking a medical leave of absence, (4) Apple may raise prices to offset foreign currency headwinds, and (5) a few disclosures about the iPhone and the App Store, which was relatively new at the time. 1222

Apple should recoup over time some of the up front expenses it incurs for the iPhone Upgrade Program. The company has two additional expenses with this program: a cost for the interest free financing that a third- party bank is providing, and an accounting expense as Apple assumes the expected resell value of the returned iPhone is less than the outstanding loan balance. When a user returns his/her iPhone and gets a new one, Apple has to pay off the loan balance on the returned iPhone and resell it (through a third- party reseller). We actually think the program is better for Apple over time since (1) it does not have to sell iPhones to wireless providers at a discount, (2) Apple's program has 100% AppleCare+ attach rate, and (3) refurbished iPhones are selling at prices where Apple is likely to end up realizing gains instead of expenses. From the filing: "The Company accounts for the trade-in right as a guarantee liability and recognizes arrangement revenue net of the fair value of such right with subsequent changes to the guarantee liability recognized within revenue." The system uses advanced sensors (lasers, radars, and cameras), which are designed to detect objects as far as two football fields away in all directions, including pedestrians, cyclists, and vehicles â€“ or even things like fluttering plastic bags and rogue birds. But the secret sauce is in the software, which is not a surprise given Googleâ€™s prowess in this area. For example, bicycles are treated as a special category of moving object. Google can identify cyclist hand signals, which allow the car to predict lane changes. Additionally, the car is designed to handle many other unique situations like construction zones and emergency vehicles. For example, when Google detects an ambulance approaching an intersection the car will remain stopped even though the light turned green. We compare the total cost of ownership (TCO) of new iPhones under Appleâ€™s plan with the device plans offered by carriers and find the iPhone Upgrade Program to be better or in line with carrier installment plan pricing. For 12 month upgraders we calculate that the iPhone Upgrade program is 9% less expensive than the cheapest carrier device plan in the market. On a 24 month basis Appleâ€™s plan is in line with the carriers. If the consumer chooses a mobile protection plan from a carrier instead of AppleCare+, the TCO under Appleâ€™s plan comes out 9% lower over a 24 month period. The only scenario where Apple is more expensive is when the user upgrades at 18 months since Apple does not allow for this in their plan and even then Appleâ€™s plan comes out just 9% higher. Note that we compare the carrier installment plans with both AppleCare+ and the carriersâ€™ own protection plans (either/or). The carrier protection plan TCOs are higher but we point out that these include the replacement of a phone (at a cost) in the case it is lost or stolen where Appleâ€™s plan does not cover this. Quick Summary of Appleâ€™s iPhone Upgrade Program Apple launched its new iPhone Upgrade Program in the US along with its announcement of the iPhone 6s and iPhone 6s Plus. The 24 month installment plan starts at $32 per month for the base level 16GB iPhone 6S, and also includes the AppleCare+ extended warranty that covers incidental damage and allows for two replacements/repairs for $79 each. After at least 12 installments, the customer gets the option to upgrade to a new iPhone and extend their payments for another two years assuming they return their old iPhone to Apple. Monthly payments range from $32.41/month for the 16GB iPhone 6S up to $44.91/month for the 128GB iPhone 6S+. We believe that Appleâ€™s Ts & Cs suggest that Citizens Bank is providing the lease financing to Apple Payment Plan customers. Consumers make their first installment of $32.41 or higher (depending on the device) through their credit card and then Citizens Bank automatically charges monthly payments under the installment loan. At any time six (6) months after the date of enrollment, consumers can become upgrade eligible by making advance payments so that they have paid the equivalent of at least twelve (12) installment payments under the installment loan. While Apple has not made this explicit we believe that the risk of default on the plan rests with Citizens Bank and not with Apple. First, we present the underlying assumptions in our user base adoption model which result in our current 2016 growth forecast of 7.9%. In this case we believe that many are missing the true size of the iPhone base as well as the size of what we call â€œnatural adoptersâ€ who use a first hand phone. In our second approach we take a top down look at the $400+ smartphone category and Appleâ€™s share in it. Here we note that this category continues to grow and that Apple has jumped to 65% share of this market as a result of the launch of larger iPhones. We believe some investors are implicitly assuming that Appleâ€™s share reverts to a mean of ~50% of this category. However, current momentum suggests that this is unlikely. In our base case we assume that the iPhone maintains its present 65% share of this category. This is particularly likely, in our opinion, given that the larger screen iPhone6/6+ should drop by $100 in price this year (that point also makes $400 the right market breakpoint for ASP in our opinion). This case results in iPhone unit growth of 5.6% in 2016 to 242.7m units. The â€œnatural adopters baseâ€ of upgraders In our September 2014 report (link), we detailed our iPhone base modelling approach. In this report, we are updating our analysis as we try to answer the question of whether iPhones can continue to grow in FY16. We believe that there is a â€œnaturalâ€ base of iPhone users that are most likely to upgrade and contribute to iPhone shipments and a â€œhanded downâ€ base of users who indirectly contribute to shipments by providing a market for used phones. The presence of a strong handed down market also suggests that the overall base size of the iPhone market is higher than some observers believe in our opinion. In Defense of Apple Summary Appleâ€™s share price declined 12.5% from its recent high of $132, following a consensus- beating F3Q15 and strong outlook into F4Q15. We believe the weakness can be attributed to fear of decelerating iPhone growth, concerns for a slowing Chinese economy, and lack of new revenue drivers. We argue that discounting Apple based on those concerns is unjustified and this note explains in detail why Apple's growth potential is under- appreciated. However, the biggest risk to our bullish thesis is a major shift in tech investor sentiment, away from smartphone-centered names. Growth in China Not Over China will overtake the US as the largest iPhone market in 2015: although Apple does not disclose unit sales by region, we estimated that Chinaâ€™s overall iPhone installed based is approaching, if not already exceeded, that of the US. IDC estimated that the US iPhone installed base will grow 12% Y/Y in 2015 to 114M units. Our estimates showed that installed base in China grew 43% Y/Y as of 2Q15, more than 3x the growth rate of the US. We estimate that the iPhoneâ€™s installed base in China has reached 111M units as of 2Q15. In reference, data analytics firm App Annie reported that China surpassed the US in iOS App Store downloads in 1Q15. If we use App Store downloads as a proxy for the installed base size, China may have exceeded the US in user base as early as 1Q15. We do not think smartphone demand in China has been â€œpulled forwardâ€ in recent quarters due to screen size upgrades. We believe the iPhoneâ€™s installed base in China will consistently grow at multiples of overall market rate, when Chinese smartphone users transition from basic, price-driven smartphone purchases, to premium, experience-driven smartphone ownership. Current iPhone installed base implies plenty of upside to Street estimates: based on our global iPhone installed base estimate of 580M, 2.25-year replacement cycle, and 90% user retention rate, we believe the current iPhone user base alone can sustainably generate 230M unit demandâ€”the same as FY15 consensus estimates of total iPhone shipment. The exhibit below shows that compared to the United States, the iPhone is significantly under-penetrated in China despite its larger share (22% vs. 7%) of the mobile user base, indicating material upside potential for new iPhone unit growth in China. Exhibit 1: Estimated 2015 iPhone Installed Base (unit in 000s) Source: IDC (October 2014), Gartner (July 2015), Oppenheimer & Co. Inc. Chinese smartphone users are upgrading to a premium experience: dynamic market conditions in China are building and breaking consumer stereotypes at less than 12-month intervals. We believe Chinese users are upgrading to mid-/high-end models and brands. 18 months ago, Xiaomi initiated a price war with its Redmi phone, dragging mid-end hardware to the $130-or-below range. Four months ago, LeTV pushed the price war to an extreme, announcing phones priced below bill-of-materials cost. LeTVâ€™s price aggression hardly helped its sales. On the contrary, we are seeing the Chinese market turning to higher ASP, premium phones. Company Update USA | Technology | IT Hardware                                               July 30, 2015 Apple Inc. (AAPL)                                                                                                                                   HOLD EQUITY RESEARCH AMERICAS Price target $135.00 Windows 10: Positive First Impressions                                                                                                       Price $122.99 Key Takeaway After running Windows 10 on a Surface Pro 3 for the last 24 hours, we like the new user interface, superior integration of touch/stylus and keyboard, as well as the seamless upgrade process from Windows 8.1 Pro. In addition to potentially posing higher competition for Macs and the upcoming iPad Pro, we think Win10 could also rekindle excitement in PCs, particularly through newer form factors like the Microsoft Surface family of products. Attractive New User Interface. We think Windows users, including those that adopted an iPad or Android Tablet due to their simpler U/I, are likely to find the new Windows 10 U/I visually appealing, well organized, and less confusing when compared to Windows 8. We found Cortana easy to set up and use, with accurate voice recognition built in. When combined with Microsoft's growing investments in Cloud Services, we think Cortana has potential to rival Google Now over time, while Apple remains further behind in this area. Superior Integration of Touch/Stylus and Keyboard. Windows 10 features a Tablet mode, which can be automatically switched by attaching or removing a keyboard. Microsoft's new Edge browser allows inking directly on webpages, a useful new feature that is not natively available in iOS or Android. We found switching applications in Tablet mode to be easier in Windows 10 compared to Windows 8. Seamless Upgrade Process. Windows 10 became available promptly as promised on 7/29, in the morning. Starting the upgrade from Windows 8.1 Pro was easy, and the entire upgrade process took only 30 minutes. Importantly, none of our preinstalled applications (including Microsoft Office, Citrix Receiver, Chrome browser, Factset, Netflix, Adobe Reader Touch, etc.) needed to be reinstalled, all of our personal data, files, and settings were migrated over, and all of the system hardware worked flawlessly after the upgrade. Potential to Rekindle Excitement in PC. Investor sentiment around PCs and expectations from Windows 10 remain low. We think potential excitement around Windows 10 would be most positive for MU, Samsung, SNDK, and INTC, with neutral to slightly negative implications for iPad and Mac. Links to Related Reports. Apple F3Q15 Preview Summary: Apple reports F3Q15 results next Tuesday (7/21), and we expect another beat-and-raise quarter driven by strong iPhone sales. This is significant given lighter than expected handset sales from Samsung. We see it as further evidence that more consumers are choosing mobile computing platforms rather than handset features. We believe Android-based devices lack a cohesive platformâ”€we continue to expect the bifurcated results to continue to become more pronounced. In fact, we believe we are seeing the beginning of the end of the Android flagship phones. Like Apple's dominance of the high-end PC market, the same is being repeated in the handset market. We would be buyers in front of the quarter. Key Points iOS Platform Attraction Will Continue to Grow: We are seeing a widening gap between iOS and Android platforms. For iOS users, Apple Pay, Apple Music, Apple TV, and Apple Watch are all seamlessly integrated with iPhones. And those integrated software and services often represent the best-in-class option for payment, music streaming, media management, and wearable. For Android users, however, we see fundamentally misaligned interests between the infrastructure provider (Google) and hardware OEMs (Samsung, LG, HTC). The disconnect between operating system and hardware, or OEMsâ€™ lack of control over handsetsâ€™ mobile operating system, will continue to exacerbate the fragmentation problem for the Android ecosystem, which has been one of the main reasons for inferior user experience on Android devices. We do not expect Appleâ€™s software and services to materially impact its top/bottom line yet, but collectively they will help sustain the share gain story for iOS devices. Growth in China: We believe fear is overblown on Chinaâ€™s recent stock market volatility and its impact on consumer spending on Apple products. We view Apple as an underpenetrated player in China. We expect two drivers to increase Appleâ€™s penetration in China: 1) major retail store expansion in the next two years (largest number of new store openings outside of the US) and 2) a more sophisticated smartphone user base that values user experience and ecosystem over hardware features. Shrinking High-end Android Share: Global tier-1 OEMs such as Samsung, LG, Motorola, Sony, and HTC proved that there is a high-end Android market based on differentiated, premium-quality hardware. Apple almost eliminated the difference (screen size), and that market is shrinking. We believe the high-end Android phones with iPhone- like ASP will continue to shrink, and the category will eventually redefine itself with lower price points similar to flagship phones made by Chinese OEMs, in the $600-and-below range. In other words, OEMs like Samsung and LG will slowly exit the Apple-like price range for their flagships, just as Chinese OEMs like Huawei and Xiaomi move up the hierarchy, but still at a discount to iPhones. This scenario is quite similar to the notebook market, where only MacBook dominates the high-end. While high-end Windows laptops do still exist, no one can ship at a scale similar to Appleâ€™s. In fact, Apple is the only one shipping â€œluxuryâ€ at scale; no one else manages to do that consistently. Apple Watch: We believe the initial sales results of Apple Watch will have minimum impact on Appleâ€™s near-term performance and our long-term bullish outlook on the product category itself. We have seen more media coverage on â€œweakeningâ€ sales momentum of the Watch. We are not concerned. First, there is no reliable, official data on Apple Watch sales; second, initial sales and shipment are poor indicators of the long-term performance. Take Appleâ€™s most successful products, iPod and iPhone, for example; within the first four months since their launch, fewer than 400,000 iPods, 1.3M iPhones were shipped. Our FY15 Apple Watch unit projection is 6M units, noticeably lower than the Streetâ€™s 9M. For FY16, our projection of 25M units is also lower than the consensus estimate of 29M units. We fully explained our long-term bullish view on Apple Watch in our in-depth analysis Watch Apple Change Computing, Again, published in April this year. Our view has not changed since. To reiterate, we believe the Watch represents the future of our mobile computing experience; the Watch is more than a piece of wearable hardware. It is an interface, a service layer between a central computing device (smartphone) and IoT (peripheral connected devices). It is better perceived as an app running in the background on our wrist, constantly listening, preparing to wake up for the user, or be triggered by other apps and devices. It is personal and contextual by nature. We see the Apple Watch as a digital "concierge"â€”the primary interface between users and a myriad of connected hardware devices consumers will add to their lives, which ultimately constitute their unique IoT ecosystems. Based on company commentary on earnings calls we estimate annual Apple TV shipments. We then assume a replacement rate of 7 years to arrive at an estimate of the total installed base. We believe that ~10m Apple TV units were shipped in 2013 given that Apple disclosed that it had revenues of ~$1bn from this segment. Apple also commented that it had total shipments of 20m in April 2014 and over 25m in January 2015. Hence, we believe shipments slowed in 2014 given the aging existing hardware combined with persistent rumors of an update coming soon. We present three different scenarios for future Apple TV shipments in Figure 2 below. Due to new gaming, HomeKit hub and TV streaming features we expect a meaningful acceleration in 2016 sales with shipments of 24m in our central case. We also calculate the penetration of Apple TV in total North American and European TVs, leveraging our prior modeling of the total TV installed base. Assuming a TV replacement period of 7 years, we estimate that AppleTV penetration was ~2.4% at the end of 2014. We expect this to increase to 5.0% in 2016 in our central case. Company Update USA | Technology | IT Hardware                                               May 31, 2015 Apple Inc. (AAPL)                                                                                                                                   HOLD EQUITY RESEARCH AMERICAS Price target $135.00 Can Cloud Services Trump Hardware?                                                                                                           Price $130.28 Google I/O 2015 Implications Key Takeaway We continue to believe Apple needs to raise its game in Cloud Services to combat competition from Google longer term. Google Now on Tap, Google Photos, and Expeditions are examples of three new services that build on Google's Cloud prowess to deliver dramatically more advanced (and economical) capabilities to virtually every Smartphone (and every classroom), rendering device hardware-based differentiation less important, particularly for growth markets in Asia. Dramatically More Advanced Cloud Services. Google Now on Tap serves up context- based intelligence, after interpreting context from a variety of different apps such as WhatsApp or Email, without requiring such apps to change. Google Photos supports natural language context-based searches, which leverage Google's 30-layer deep neural network learning algorithms running in the Cloud. Expeditions brings virtual-reality field trips to virtually every classroom, again leveraging Google's investments and innovation in Cloud technology. Advances in data compression and web-page rendering optimization for slower connections also make the internet more accessible to the next wave of mobile users from less developed markets in Asia or Africa. Google Now on Tap = Lower App or OS Fragmentation. Apple's iOS app ecosystem is revered as a money-making machine by developers. While we believe Google's Play Store revenues are growing faster (off a lower base) than iOS app store, Google Now on Tap signals a more fundamental shift away from a litany of apps powered by disconnected data sources, to a more context-aware and unified Cloud Service that over time could make device-based apps less relevant. At ~1m apps each, we think the last thing either iOS or Android ecosystems need is new apps. With fewer apps to install/update, or to switch across, we think user experience could improve dramatically. This in turn would also minimize divergence in capabilities across different versions of the Android OS installed on devices. Can Cloud Services Trump Hardware? As mobile usage models increasingly migrate to the Cloud, catalyzed by growing adoption of hardware-lite devices like Smartwatches, we expect more of the user experience to be increasingly driven by superior Cloud Services such as Google Now. This represents a longer term threat to Apple's hardware-centric business model. In the near term, we expect AAPL stock to remain well supported by positive China iPhone data points, and ongoing share repurchases. We wouldn't be surprised if Apple announced advancements in Cloud Services at WWDC. Expect Transition to Flexible Display. While mobile device-based differentiation overall would be challenged by growing importance of Cloud Services, we think device form factor innovation driven by flexible display is likely to prove more important over time, as a key enabler of new consumption models for next-generation Cloud Services. Investors should consider this report as only a single factor in making their investment decision. www.jpmorganmarkets.com 21 Rod Hall, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-415) 315-6713          07 May 2015 rod.b.hall@jpmorgan.com Tax Structure Through an Irish tax entity Apple, like other major corporates, has shielded itself from taxes for a large part of its overseas earnings. This is effectively accomplished via AOI or Apple Operations International which is an un-taxed entity. AOI has this special status because of a peculiarity in Irish tax law (some say there by design) which only taxes entities based on where management control resides. The structure is more complex than this with multiple other Irish entities involved including Apple Sales International (ASI) and Apple Operations Europe (AOE). The US Senate Permanent Subcomittee on Investigations questioned Apple on its tax structure back in May of 2013 and much of the information we have on the structure comes from documents associated with this as well as the European Commission investigation â€“ which we believe may have been prompted by the US investigation. In this section we lay out the structure to help you better understand how Apple is shielding most of their international profits from taxation. Apple Inc Apple Inc. is the US taxpaying entity responsible for coordinating sales in the Americas and Appleâ€™s Irish subsidiaries. Apple Inc. conducts its offshore operations through a network of offshore affiliates. The key affiliates at the top of the offshore network are companies that are incorporated in Ireland. Apple Inc. owns the legal and economic rights to all Intellectual Property (IP) developed by Apple employees worldwide. Apple Inc. also has a cost sharing agreement with two of its Irish entities, ASI and AOE. The cost sharing agreement allows Apple Inc to allocate R&D costs to these entities in proportion to international revenue generated at each entity. For example, in FY11, Apple generated ~60% of its sales outside the Americas. As a result these Irish entities share ~60% of R&D costs with Apple Inc. While this agreement has the effect of increasing Apple Inc profits and associated taxes it also allows the international subsidiaries to sell products and retain profits from these sales overseas without paying US taxes on them. Overview of Key Irish Subsidiaries and Org Structure Apple Operations International is incorporated in Ireland, but is non-tax resident in the country. Ireland allows for incorporated entities to be treated as non-tax resident if most of their operations are controlled by management sitting outside Ireland. According to US laws, an entity is non-taxable if it is incorporated outside the US. This difference in laws between the US and Ireland defining taxable entities has allowed Apple to set up AOI as a non-taxable entity for both the US and Ireland even though it has links to both countries. According to documents provided during the US Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations hearing (US PSI report), Apple Inc owns 100% of AOI, either directly or indirectly through other controlled foreign corporations. AOI, incorporated in Ireland in 1980, is the ultimate owner of most of Appleâ€™s other offshore entities. 2 22 Rod Hall, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-415) 315-6713          07 May 2015 rod.b.hall@jpmorgan.com From 2009 to 2012, AOI received $29.9bn in dividends from lower-tiered offshore affiliates, AOE and ASI. According to Apple, AOIâ€™s net income made up 30% of Appleâ€™s total worldwide net profits from 2009-2011. AOI is the parent company of AOE, a subsidiary incorporated in Ireland. AOE is, in turn, the parent company of ASI, another subsidiary incorporated in Ireland again. AOE and ASI only pay Irish tax on business carried out in Ireland. While there are other subsidiaries in Ireland, AOE and ASI are the two key entities that we believe are important for understanding Appleâ€™s international tax structure. Figure 1: Apple: Offshore Organizational Structure Source: US Senate Permanent Subcommittee On Investigations report. AOE According to relevant public documents published by the European Commission, AOE is a 100% subsidiary of AOI and is an Irish incorporated non-tax resident company carrying on a trade through a branch in Ireland. The main activity of AOEâ€™s Irish branch is the manufacture of Apple products based on disclosures in EC documents. AOE theoretically purchases materials from related companies and sells manufactured products to other related companies. AOEâ€™s Irish branch also provides shared services to Apple companies in EMEA, including payroll services, centralized purchasing and a customer call center. AOE is party to a cost sharing agreement whereby, together with other Apple Inc. subsidiaries, it shares R&D costs and risks of developing certain Apple products. Apple Inc holds the legal title to all Apple IP, while AOE has subsidiary economic IP rights under this cost sharing agreement. 3 23

(AAPL)                                                                                                                                   HOLD EQUITY RESEARCH AMERICAS Price target $135.00 Apple Pay is Killer App for Apple Watch                                                                                                      Price $128.95 Key Takeaway Jefferies mobile payments analyst Jason Kupferberg's work reinforces our view that Apple Pay is likely to be one of the most compelling killer apps for Apple Watch. As consumer awareness grows through 1) broader merchant acceptance of Apple Pay, and 2) higher competition from Samsung Pay and Google Wallet, we expect Apple and Samsung to benefit the most from higher penetration of their premium mobile devices capable of mobile payments. Apple Pay is Killer App for Apple Watch. We think the convenience of using Apple Pay on Apple Watch with or without a tethered iPhone, while ensuring a higher level of security and privacy as compared to using physical credit cards, is likely to gain traction as a smarter way to pay. "Apple Pay 2.0" with browser-based payments and loyalty card support, as described by Jason Kupferberg (see our mobile payments franchise note linked below), would further increase the relevance and persistence of Apple Pay. By the end of 2016, we estimate that roughly 90% of the global iPhone installed base would be Apple Pay (NFC) capable (see Chart 1). We expect Apple Watch penetration to also steadily increase over that period, in some cases as an accessory to an older iPhone 5/5s/5c. More broadly speaking, we expect Apple Watch to become a convenient and secure repository of electronic credentials not just for mobile payments, but also for identity/authentication across a variety of usage scenarios - e.g. airline boarding passes, membership cards, hotel room key, or even Enterprise access. Expect Competition from Samsung Pay in 2H15. On its 1Q15 earnings call Samsung described Samsung Pay as "triple secured" through 1) fingerprint, 2) secure element, and 3) Samsung KNOX. Samsung plans to roll out Samsung Pay in Korea and the U.S. in 2H15. We also expect future Samsung Smartwatches to integrate Samsung Pay. Since Samsung Pay integrates both NFC-based, and conventional magstripe-based payment technologies, we think it could potentially see broader adoption than Apple Pay (NFC only), and accelerate consumer awareness of mobile payments. Expect Virtuous Cycle of Mobile Payments to Benefit Apple and Samsung. We think direct contribution from Apple Pay is unlikely to be an EPS needle mover for Apple. Instead, we think the convenience of Apple Pay would drive increased adoption of iPhone and Apple Watch. We expect Apple Pay and Samsung Pay to serve as unique differentiators that other Smartphone/Watch makers would find difficult to match. Links to Related Reports. New iPad apps developed in collaboration with IBM increase iPad's relevance in vertical applications such as financial markets, utilities, government, healthcare, industrial, insurance, retail, telco, and travel, consistent with our expectations (see prior note linked here: Enterprise Ecosystem Progress â€“ Maintain Hold). We think the largest such untapped opportunity probably lies within the healthcare industry, which when combined with the health-monitoring capabilities built into the Apple Watch, we think represents a major new potential market for Apple (IBM has estimated global healthcare spending in the $7 trillion range) longer term. Additionally, with enhancements such as iOS Extensions (see Chart 13), we believe Apple is trying to make the iPad more relevant in a traditional Enterprise environment, as an alternative to Wintel PCs. This is an area where the iPad has not seen impressive penetration, except as an optional/additional device incapable of replacing a primary Enterprise PC. We think availability of Microsoft Office for iPad also dramatically increases the Enterprise utility of iPad (see our case study in Charts 19 to 23). Meanwhile, introduction of Microsoftâ€™s Surface 3 at the $499 price point represents a big step forward by Wintel, in closing the price gap relative to iPad, while delivering superior Enterprise capabilities. Also, Samsungâ€™s KNOX closes Android security gaps to deliver a robust and secure Enterprise solution, building on flexibility inherent in Android. We believe iPad was originally                     Chart 1: iPad is Changing for Enterprise intended to be a consumer platform, which it has been very successful at. Watch Apple Change Computing, Again Our last report, â€œHow to Think About the Watchâ€ (link), garnered a lot of questions around our belief that the Watch will act as the â€œdigital conciergeâ€ of oneâ€™s devices. The most common question wasâ€“what does â€œconcierge of devicesâ€ mean? This report attempts to answer that question and present our theory of everythingâ€¦Apple. Key Points ï‚·    Software/Internet Services-Harbingers of a Paradigm Shift: On the software and internet services side of things, decentralization happened much earlier than hardware. The advent of the smartphone and apps enabled consumers to customize their own computing experience so that it could be drastically different from the next personâ€™s. Whereas in hardware, device convergence is still ongoing and signs of higher level customization and divergence are only beginning to surface. See Exhibit 5. ï‚·    The Monopoly of Smartphone: In the more mature stage of TV and desktop PC, they evolved to be connected with many peripheral hardware pieces (think home theater in the case of TV, or MP3 players, digital camera, and PDA in the case of PC)â€”a form of decentralization. Todayâ€™s smartphone does everything by itself, but we think that model will change soon as consumers begin adopting IoT devices. ï‚·    Dethroning the Smartphone: The mobile computing experience, on the hardware level, is not as customized as on the software level. In our view, several factors contribute to this: access to funds for hardware start-ups, economies of scale, and the need for a unifying interface. With many of those barriers removed over the past few years, we still have not seen a strong uptick in hardware. The one thing missing is the interfaceâ€”we have it now: the Watch. We believe the Apple Watch will lead consumers into an age of decentralized hardware in the next five years. The Watch will usher in the next age of computing. Bottom Line: For the watch to be a success, it will, over time, have to change user behavior for the next phase of computingâ€”not only mobile (current generation), but also ubiquitous (next generation). We have gone from spending hours on a PC to spending minutes on smartphonesâ€“in the next stage of human-computer interaction, we believe users will be spending seconds instead of minutes or hours dealing with electronic devices. This will be facilitated by a notification-based interface on the Watch. 2 353 Apple Inc. â€œStrangely Familiarâ€ Rarely does the general public get Apple products right at first sight, before their actual shipment. Looking back at Appleâ€™s first generation product launches (iPod, iPhone, and iPad), one thing becomes clear: each product begged the question: what does it do? Below are some reviews/quotes that followed the product announcements. First iPod (announced in October 2001): â€œClearly Apple is following Sony's lead by integrating consumer electronics devices into its marketing strategy, but Apple lacks the richness of Sony's product offering. And introducing new consumer products right now is risky, especially if they cannot be priced attractivelyâ€¦â€ (Technology Business Research, October 2001) First iPhone (announced in January 2007): â€œThe keyboard more or less requires "faith" in the word auto-correction, an Apple rep likened it to using The Force, and while all three reviewers were able to get up to speed sooner or later, it's most certainly agreed that this is no BlackBerry- killer.â€ (Engadget, review of other journalistâ€™s iPhone reviews, June 2007) â€œFive hundred dollars? Fully subsidized? With a plan? That is the most expensive phone in the world. And it doesnâ€™t appeal to business customers because it doesnâ€™t have a keyboard, which makes it not a very good email machine.â€ (Steve Ballmer, 2007) First iPad (announced in January 2010): â€This time around the Next Big Thing is called an iPad. It's basically an oversize iPod Touchâ€¦ Jobs and his team kept using words like â€œbreakthroughâ€ and â€œmagicalâ€, but the iPad is neither, at least not right nowâ€¦At the very least, we had hoped a tablet from Apple would do something new, something we've never seen before. That's not the caseâ€¦â€ (Newsweek, January 2010) Not that we think we get it right all the timeâ€”but in this report, we attempt to at least â€œthink differentâ€. We believe all products are built to solve problems, some obvious, some less so. When a problem is less obvious, designers need to ask the right questions and correctly frame the problem, then find a solution. The reason opinions are divided on the Watch, is that it solves both existing problems (time-keeping, fitness tracking) and problems we donâ€™t know exist (new ways to connect to people and potentially to other devices). Itâ€™s this second question that Apple tends to get right, and early reviews tend not to answer. Current smart watch products, mostly miniature smartphones in disguise, educate consumers poorly on new possibilities. We find it interesting that Apple never uses adjectives like â€œsmartâ€, or â€œintelligentâ€ to describe the Watch. We believe this is a carefully considered choice made by Apple, because, contrary to smartphones, computing-related problems are not priorities for the Watch. What we believe Apple does best is improving the human interface for electronic devices (mouse for Mac, Touch Pad for MacBook, Click Wheel for iPod, and multi-touch for iPhone). When a product is launched consumers, bloggers, analysts, and journalists tend to compare it to familiar, existing products (iPod vs. MP3 player; iPhone vs. Blackberry). What we learn in retrospect is that the actual products are anything but. This is because the new interface introduces new possibilities that escape the imagination of the general 3 354

Company Update USA | Technology | IT Hardware                                             March 9, 2015 Apple Inc. (AAPL)                                                                                                                                   HOLD EQUITY RESEARCH AMERICAS Price target $124.00 Apple Watch: Fashion Forward                                                                                                                   Price $127.14 Key Takeaway We found today's Apple Watch update roughly consistent with our and investor expectations, with hardly any surprises. We think this is the first time since the iPod, that Apple might have introduced a new product category without dramatically raising the technology or capability bar over competition, particularly from Samsung. We expect Apple Pay, and fitness/health tracking to serve as the killer applications. Expect Health/Fitness Tracking to Become a Killer App. Over the last few months of continuously using the Samsung Gear S Smartwatch, we have found its pedometer, heart-rate sensor, and location/distance/elevation measurements to be particularly useful in generating high resolution exercise/activity tracking data, which we think could be further enhanced with measurements for other types of health data, including blood pressure, blood glucose, etc. to provide a more complete picture of one's health/fitness. With integrated standalone communications capabilities as in the Samsung Gear S, we foresee a higher level of consumer interest in fitness/health applications in the future, including the capability to communicate seamlessly and securely with qualified medical and fitness industry professionals, who would be armed with vital data from the Smartwatch to enable more frequent and tailored guidance. Fashion Forward: Possible upside to Apple Watch ASP. We believe our Apple Watch ASP estimate of $400 is approximately in line with the Street's; however, given the $549 starting price for the standard stainless steel version of the Apple Watch, and materially higher-priced lifestyle/fashion-focused offerings, we think there could be upside to our Apple Watch ASPs. We continue to model Apple Watch shipments of ~16m units in FY15 (vs. Street range of 8m to 41m, and Fubon 15m). Pre-orders and previews (at Apple Stores) for the Apple Watch are expected to begin on April 10th and the Watch is expected to become available starting April 24th in 9 countries (including China). Our checks indicate difficulties with the casing and display might be causing delays. Our build plan checks also indicate a significant skew toward lower-end models.
