Itâ€™s interior decorating. Itâ€™s the fabric of the curtains and the sofa. But to me, nothing could be further from the meaning of design. Design is the fundamental soul of a man-made creation that ends up expressing itself in successive outer layers of the product or service.â€ -Steve Jobs, CNNMoney/Fortune, January 24, 2000 In this note, we focus on the upcoming Apple Watch (â€œthe Watchâ€ hereinafter) and explain our understanding and expectation for its differentiation, positioning, competitive advantage, and its role in the entire Apple ecosystem. We are very optimistic on the Watchâ€™s long-term market potential and see it as an object of utility, affection, and luxury that represents the next step in our â€œmobile firstâ€ future. We also raise our price target and financial estimates for Apple based on more bullish outlook on its product cycle. Key Points ï‚·    Better Interface Always Wins: We believe superior understanding and expertise of human interface designs are Appleâ€™s core competency. While Apple is shackled by the same limitation of battery power and chip speed, human interface innovations on the Watch will make it fundamentally more feature-rich, user-friendly, and elegant than the competition. ï‚·    The Watch Has Three Roles: We believe the Watch will take three roles: an object of utility, affection, and luxury. The Watch is first an efficient extension of the smartphone, second, a facilitator of intimate personal communications, and lastly a high margin product that provides substantial revenue and margin upside to AAPL. ï‚· th March 9th Event Preview: We expect Appleâ€™s March 9 press event to be centered around the Watch, from which we expect details on apps, new features, hardware, sales strategies, and shipment timing. We also expect Apple to release a refreshed MacBook Air and Apple TV. Lastly, we believe a music streaming service merging iTunes Radio and Beats Music will come online sometime in 1H15 (also possible at WWDC in June). ï‚·    Model Update: We raise our price target from $130 to $155. Our revised estimates are driven by higher revenue contribution from iPhone and the Watch, margin improvement from better mix, and strong FY16 outlook in emerging markets. The long-term price target of $155 is based on 13 times FY16 EPS of $9.76 plus $25 per share net cash. We believe our estimates are conservative. ï‚·    Risks to Our Thesis: Key risks to our thesis include lower than expected iPhone shipment in FY16 (successor to iPhone 6 and 6 Plus), lower than expected margin and Apple Watch shipment, unexpected margin pressure from material cost and FX volatility, higher than expected spending in operations, and lower than expected growth in China. 2 586 Apple Inc. Human Interface above All Human interface is at the center of all Apple products: we think of Apple as a human- centric, technology product development company. As we explained in our first report on Apple in September (link), Apple, like no other consumer electronics makers, has always set human interface as one of the highest priorities in its product development. Almost all of its â€œrock starâ€ products are associated with major breakthroughs in human interface features. Apple Watch is no exception to this rule. When the Watch was introduced in September 2014, we saw what we expected, and much more. Apple Watch brings new human interface designs and user experience features that achieve two important goals: 1) expanding the physical limitation of hardware; and 2) bringing more â€œhuman touchâ€ to a device that interact with users more intimately. Good human interface design provide a better user experience and makes more efficient use of hardware resources (display size and CPU power). This is especially important as devices gets smaller with more constrained resources and more personal touches. Also, as devices becomes more personal with users, the interface is required to deliver more â€œaffectionâ€ more â€œfunctionsâ€. Inc. If the success of Pebble and more recently, Pebble Time, has taught us anything, it is that spec is almost irrelevant for smart watches. Pure pursuit of performance is bound to end badly with serious compromised battery life. The small size determined that OEMs have to think harder for the most compelling use cases and make difficult compromises balancing performance and user experience. In fact, we can see this in the adoption of android smart watches or lack thereof. Pebble adopts a differentiated customer centric approach. We believe Pebble alone (including orders for Pebble Time) has outsold all other Android Wear based products combined. We see little innovation in smart watches running Android Wear. The operating system is essentially a miniaturized smartphone interface, with inefficient use of display (round watch face) and poor readability. However, Apple Watch breaks the physical limitation of a watch to various degrees by introducing new ways for users to interact with the devices. Apple Is a Platform Company It offers the best devices at what it considers a fair price. The company focuses on providing users a superior experience through well-integrated and innovative hardware, software, services, and ecosystem. As a result, its users are the most loyal, and they tend to purchase multiple Apple devices. This is best reflected in the iPhone, where the company has kept pricing steady in the last few years even as competitors had to half their pricing to compete. Services to see revenue growth inflection and margin expansion in CY15, due to Apple Pay, App Store and iCloud. We believe Apple Pay can grow from 1% of Services revenue in CY15 to 14% in CY17, with 100% incremental operating margins. Services should become even more important in the future, both as a platform differentiator and revenue and profitability generator. We see many future opportunities, especially in streaming music, HealthKit, HomeKit and CarPlay. And increasingly, Apple may control less of the hardware and focus more on software and services. Developers and merchants generate at least 2x as much revenue on iOS vs. Android, even though Android ships more units, due to better iOS user demographics and easier-to-use devices. With multiple new partnership opportunities in media content (iTunes, Beats, Apple TV), health, home, cars, etc., we believe this will continue to strengthen Apple's platform. Devices Apple users are loyal as 89% of iPhone users plan to buy another iPhone. We believe Apple's device installed base, including 415M+ iPhone users, is much stickier than some investors realize. Our latest survey in the US, Apple's largest market, indicated 89% of current iPhone users plan to buy another iPhone. In China, Apple's second largest market, 75% of iPhone users plan to buy another iPhone, and loyalty increased significantly from 60% about a year ago. We believe loyalty increases for the market leaders as the market matures, as evidenced by the US data. Users gain familiarity with one ecosystem over time, and get locked in as they store, synchronize and share more data on the platform and purchase more devices (â€œhalo effectâ€), apps and media. 4 621 Apple, Inc. | March 2, 2015 Exhibit 1: Apple Has the Most Loyal Customers in the US (Measured as % of Current Users Who Plan to Purchase Another Phone from the Same Brand) So u rce: Alp h aW ise Su rvey Decemb er 2014, Mo rgan Stan ley Research Exhibit 2: Apple Brand Loyalty in China Also Market-Leading and Growing So u rce: Alp h aW ise Su rvey Au gu st 2014, Mo rgan Stan ley Research Apple's customers are willing to pay a premium for better user experience. Apple Watch Adoption Scenarios We have developed three scenarios for Apple Watch adoption in order to give readers some idea of the sensitivity of our earnings model to different potential outcomes. We have selected a central case which includes addressable base penetration of 5% by the end of 2015 moving to 13% by the end of CYâ€™16. However, we are still missing key features of the device like battery life that could impact the speed of adoption. The inclusion of this Central case in our forecasts increases our CYâ€™15 EPS forecast by 6% to $9.46 and our CYâ€™16 forecast by 12% to $11.02. As we note below this is based on what we feel is a conservative view that the EBIT contribution margin for the Sport model will be just in line with group average margins. Central Case Penetration Scenario We assume the Apple Watch penetrates 5% of the addressable user base by the end of CY15 moving up to 13% of the addressable base by CY16. This equates to 26m Watch shipments in 2015 and 55m in 2016. Morgan estimates. In our Central penetration case, we show the impact of variations in margins and mix of watches on our previous CY15 and CY16 EPS estimates. As stated above, our Apple EPS estimate moves by ~6% to $9.46 for CY15 and by ~12% to $11.02 for CY16, assuming most of the watches to be sold will be the Sport version at a base price of $349 with 31% EBIT contribution margin. We discuss our profit margin assumptions below. Margin assumptions by Apple Watch model We lay out our margin assumptions for the Apple Watch in Table 2 below. We begin with our assumptions for the pricing of the Stainless Steel ($1,000) and Gold ($4,000) versions of the Watch. While Apple has announced the $349 price for the 3 676 Rod Hall, CFA             North America Equity Research (1-415) 315-6713          11 February 2015 rod.b.hall@jpmorgan.com aluminum Sport model they have not said how they will price higher end models. However, we believe that Apple intends to promote their higher end Watches as luxury products and is, therefore, likely to price them as such. In terms of BoM for the Watch we are using a slightly higher $105 for the Sport model than we believe products like the Samsung Gear Live carry. We make a rough materials cost adjustment for the Stainless (+$95) and Gold (+$695) models. Morgan Our next step is to assume a gross margin contribution for the Sport model of 45%. This is above Apple's current group average GM of ~39% though Implied Other Device costs within GM are notoriously difficult to estimate. Our 45% assumption yields implied other costs within GM of $88/device which we assume are the same regardless of model. We next assume incremental opex of $50/device which yields an EBIT contribution margin for the Sport model of 31% - similar to Appleâ€™s group average margin. We note that this $50/device assumption could prove conservative given it is not obvious where Apple needs to incur significant additional cost to bring the device to market. Due to this we believe the key risk to our analysis is that Apple generates materially more margin than we have assumed in any of our cases. Also note that the EBIT margin contribution from both the Stainless and Gold versions is likely far higher than the Sport version. Later in this report we show how various mix assumption affect Apple earnings but suffice it to say that more of these luxury models in the mix, if we are in the ballpark on pricing, can have a large impact on margin contribution. 4 677

We expect iPhone share gains and growth re- acceleration driven by larger screen iPhones based on our AlphaWise surveys and supply chain checks. Apple       report. 1 114 Apple, Inc. | January 20, 2015 MORGAN STANLEY RESEARCH has guided below consensus in six of the last eight quarters by an average of 6% at the mid-point of the guidance range. This would imply a $50B mid-point for this quarter, though we would not be surprised if the range is $3B-wide instead of the $2B historically given uncertainties around the likely launch of a new product category (Watch) and large foreign exchange movements. However, given the upside in iPhones and downside in iPads mentioned above and the new Watch, we could see gross margin guidance bracket consensus of 38.6% or show ~50bps of upside versus December quarter guidance. We model 39.0%. Apple's gross margin guidance at the mid-point has been in-line or slightly better than consensus for the last four quarters. Watch and foreign exchange create some uncertainty. We model 3M Watch shipments in the March quarter, adding $1.4B of revenue. However, Apple management historically embeds conservative assumptions in their guidance for new products, especially products that have yet to launch. Forecasts from Morgan Stanley's FX strategists indicate a 5.7-point Y/Y headwind to Apple's March quarter revenues. While we believe the company will hedge and adjust pricing in some regions (as it has for the App Store in Europe and iPhones in Russia), exchange rates is a bigger headwind than recent quarters. Also note Apple will not report iPod or Watch units going forward as they are part of the Other Products line. We remain Overweight Apple. Key debates in 2015 center around sustainability of iPhone demand, potential impact of Watch, and margin expansion. Our surveys and analyses indicate strong demand for the larger screen iPhones, and a large, aging installed base that will refresh. We believe Watch expectations remain too pessimistic. Our surveys and industry conversations indicate strong interest in wearables, especially Apple's Watch. Net, we see some unit upside vs. consensus iPhone and Watch estimates but especially against conservative gross margin estimates (38.5% in FY15, -10bps Y/Y). We believe growing revenue streams from iPhone, Watch, Beats headphones, Apple Pay all have better than corporate average gross margins, while declining revenue streams from iPad and iPod have lower gross margins. With strong iPhone and Watch unit demand and improving gross margins, we remain Overweight. Evercore ISI Research The Apple Watch is a timepiece, communication and health monitoring device. Recognizing size/usage constraints, its Watch OS introduces a new user interface (UI), innovative methods of navigation (e.g., Digital Crown), Force Touch (adding degrees to the touch-screenâ€™s z-axis to differentiate between a light tap vs. deep press; a feature we expect to make its way into future iPads, iPhones), integrates Siri (we expect a smartwatchâ€™s limited real estate only increases the value of voice recognition), Health monitoring sensors and supports Apple Pay. The Apple Watch is expressly designed to pair with a userâ€™s iPhone using onboard Wi-Fi 802.11b/g and Bluetooth 4.0, making it an â€œaccessoryâ€ as the iPhone does most of the heavy- lifting (e.g., processing app code, making calls, etc.). On-board storage and Bluetooth mean the Apple Watch can be used as a standalone music player. Apple Watch will be available in three collections, based on material of enclosure: 1.    Apple Watch = stainless steel w/ retina display covered in scratch-resistant sapphire crystal 2.    Apple Watch Sport = anodized aluminum enclosure w/ retina display made lightweight and scratch-resistant by using aluminosilicate glass (Ion-X glass) 3.    Apple Watch Edition = 18-karat gold w/ retina display covered in scratch-resistant sapphire crystal Each watch will come in two sizes â€“ 38 mm and 42 mm â€“ and we believe Apple recognizes a watch communicates a userâ€™s self-expression as much as it provides utility, so Watches offer some personalization (e.g., in contrast to Appleâ€™s typical product strategy of tightly-limited SKUs), available in multiple colors and models, using multiple detachable band options. Watches offer various changeable faces.
